text.text: I’ve had their “Tommy Salame” before. It was adequately sized and normally priced for the quality you’re getting. This time I got the “Chicken Parm Sando.” I would say it was truly overpriced for the quantity you are getting. $21 for a small 6 inch sub makes no sense even if all the ingredients maybe organic or better quality. I would have priced that at $16 maximum because I know their overhead costs may be on the higher end. I just was expecting a bigger and more filling sandwich for that hefty price tag. Overall, it tasted great and homemade which I appreciate. However, it was a bit too acidic per my preference leaving me with some heartburn. I also got the $4 “Rye Brownie.” It had a more dark chocolate flavor and the texture was more wet like fudge rather than pillowy softness. I also experienced some heartburn from that. I wanted to purchase a tiny box of a single serving chocolate covered honeycomb but it was priced at $20. I mean online the “Honeymoon” brand sells it $12.50 each. I just found everything on their shelves from chocolates to jams priced double or triple what you would pay for elsewhere all to appease their rent and salaries. I really like their dedication to quality and freshness. And it’s truly an aesthetically pleasing atmosphere. They just need to work on adequately pricing their food and products according to the market.

text.text:
We had a wonderful brunch experience at Agnes! The cheese board was definitely the highlight, offering a great selection of cheeses with enough variety to keep things interesting and never repetitive. It felt like the perfect way to start the meal. Since it was brunch, we also ordered toast and salad. The crème brûlée toast stood out it was sweet, indulgent, and quite filling, almost like having dessert for breakfast. On the lighter side, the Babé Farms Lettuces salad was beautifully done, with fresh mixed greens paired with Aries cheese, smoked almonds, and dates, all tied together with a mustard shallot vinaigrette. The combination of crunchy nuts and sweet dates made it both refreshing and satisfying.

The atmosphere of the restaurant is another big plus. With exposed brick walls, high ceilings, and a spacious patio, it feels open and stylish, yet still comfortable and welcoming. The way the dining room, bar, and market space flow together makes it feel unique and versatile. I also appreciated how extensive the menu is there are options for breakfast, brunch, lunch, and dinner, which makes it a place you could easily visit again and again for different occasions. On top of that, the drink selection is varied enough to complement any meal. Overall, Agnes is a spot that delivers not only on flavor but also on ambiance and versatility.

text.text:
Three of us took a friend for her 30th birthday based on a recommendation. However, it didn't live up to the hype. We went on Saturday night, 7:30 p.m. reservation. We got seated about 10 minutes after our reservation time which was expected. A server offered to take our drink order within a few minutes. Then another one went up to our table for the same purpose only a few minutes after the original order. With one vegetarian in the group, we attempted to order a mix of entrees that offered something for everyone. The Cheese Board was too small for four hungry women who had just gotten massages. The Crispy Tater Tots tasted just like any other, minus the crispy. The Beets and Pears was meh. The Grilled Cauliflower wasn't available but they made it with broccolini and that was okay. Unfortunately, there weren't any distinguishing seasonings or flavors that stood out. The carnivores ordered the fried chicken and skirt steak. They said it was good. We each one cocktail which didn't wow anyone. While we asked the server for her assessment on whether she thought we had ordered enough and she said it was a lot of food. It wasn't given the family-style service and small portions. There was a long delay between each order, including our drinks. We found ourselves done in between orders as we looked toward the kitchen area hoping to see a server with one of our orders.

Since we were celebrating a birthday, we asked to see the dessert menu which was very unimpressive (root beer float, some kind of bread pudding, sorbet and some chocolate taco). We assumed that they would bring some kind of dessert for the birthday girl but no such luck. She did, however, get a birthday card as soon as she sat down. I would recommend this if one wants a light meal with loud ambiance in a restaurant-deli ambiance. I will not be returning for a light meal nor a dinner as the food and service were nothing spectacular, especially for a tab of $326.72.

text.text:
We came here for the band "Rainbow Girls" and it was a great time and was enjoyed by all, but the angle of the grass was steeple and the lawn was bumpy, (but i'm old).  We got there early and had dinner.  They had excellent vegan options and other plant forward food.

Our table ordered the chicken katsu sandwich, the fried cauliflower tacos (order without kimchi sauce for a vegan option), and my dish, the boho bowl.  It all was fresh bright.   The chips that went with the sandwich were flavored with vinegar and a bit too zingy for our palate.

The boho bowl was full of flavor and variety, yummy lentils, brown rice, greens, beets, grilled broccoli, pickled onions, and a wonderful chimmichuri sauce.

The store had a very well thought out variety of items for sale, including books and boutique pantry items that are some of the newest items on the market.

There is a grab and go area near the front with food.  You can eat inside or outside.

There is even a clay studio inside.  I didn't find out about it, but it looked fun.  The surroundings were fabulous.  The sun went down right in front of us, behind the trees

I would love to come back for an experience that includes more than music, even though my butt hurts, lol!!!

text.text: Incredible location tucked in between the upscale hotel block in Oceanside. Standing out with gorgeous artwork on the building, Always Hungry immediately draws you in! A wide variety of vegan and gluten free products ~ as well as tinned fish, eggs, chips, crackers ~ you name it ~ they’ve got it. And they’re specifically sourcing the best quality items which takes the pain out of shopping! Prepared section has everything you need and chef-curated — local farms are highlighted here — There’s even a selection of produce at the ready, beautifully displayed in wooden and ceramic bowls. There’s more! Tons of organic wines. Pastas. Rice. Candies. Mocktails. Kombucha ON TAP! Raw Milk. Decorative items for your tablescape. And tons of other gems. A haven for chefs, foodies, tourists, and locals for all your goods. The owner knows what’s up! Just go, you won’t regret it.

text.text:
This local business is one of our weekly faves to stop into.
I have vegan friends who also love this place, and it's where we go to find great foodie gifts for people who appreciate locally-sourced and great quality goods.
We always find something new to try out, thanks to clever curation by the owner, who we've been getting to know because we are there so regularly.
She has impeccable taste, and we can always trust that there will be an endless variety of freshies on the shelves and in the fridge there.
A big bonus for us, since we already fell in love with the place, is that Always Hungry participates in the local business app called REPEGS, so we get to save money every visit, plus REPEGS donates to local charities we care about (without any additional cost to us).
It's a win/win/win for our small-town local economy, the hard-working entrepreneurs here, and us customers.
I highly recommend this spot...it's a must if you are anywhere in North San Diego County/downtown Oceanside (great location right by the Oceanside Pier and beach as well)!

text.text:
I have a bad habit of going to BakeSum too late in the day even though I know they always sell out pretty quick! Get there bright and early or pre-order if you're looking to get a good amount of pastries.

We went this past Saturday in hopes of our favorite, the Okonomiyaki Danish. It has a buttery layered pastry with a soft boiled egg in the middle-- heaven! But we were too late. Thankfully, they were making a fresh batch of their Black Sesame and Coconut Ube cookies. Of course we had to get a cookie! I also go for the Coconut Ube, it's not too sweet & coconut pairs so well with Ube. The cookie itself is also slightly crispy on the edges and has a lovely chewy middle.

We also grabbed a Matchamisu! It was our first time trying it and it won't be our last. The perfect amount of matcha is infused into the cream layers while the coffee soaked layers don't overpower the matcha. And, best of all, it's not too sweet!

This past visit was the first time I noticed their day-olds basket. Sadly, it was also empty, but I love businesses that offer this! Rather than toss everything at the end of the day, they package items that are slightly more shelf stable and sell them at a discounted cost.

I always enjoy being greeted by the staffs chorus of "welcome in!" & pink cafe aesthetic, it really just sets such a great tone for my day!

Next time, I'll be sure to get there early so I can finally get my hands on that danish again! (Also they're dog friendly! They have a jar of dog treats by the window for your furry friends)

text.text: Wanted to get some desserts. Found this spot, ended up getting the Jasmine milk bun, Pandan milk bun, and Yuzu Meringue Bun.  My sis said the Jasmine milk bun was Jasmining. I have the Pandan milk bun, it was so good, the Pandan cream inside the bun was gooooood.  If you ever had a concha, it’s  an elevated concha with Asian flavors. I had a piece of the Yuzu meringue Bun,  the Yuzu flavor came with a punch.  Strong Yuzu flavor. I’m more of a savory person but these desserts hit the spot.  The staff were nice and welcoming.  There was a line when we got there but it went by pretty fast. There are  about 4 tables outside the store where you can enjoy these bomb.com desserts.  Would recommend coming here.  Parking is a little tough but we were able to find something.  If you looking for a spot to walk around Lake Merritt is literally a few blocks away.

text.text: I recently visited Suprette, which has taken over the space formerly occupied by Dandy's. It's a delightful transformation! Suprette offers the beloved cakes and baked goods that Baker's & Baristas is known for, along with a curated selection of other goodies, including books, sauces, and treats. A must-try is their milk & cereal cake (tres leches)—it's always worth picking up. Whether you're looking for a sweet treat or unique finds, Suprette is a great addition to the area. Highly recommended!

text.text:
Can’t wait to come back for a positive review after my first be bright pour-over as I think I had the best bean in North America and haven’t had a good quality of Geisha for long time.
I dropped by for a cold brew and grabbed a bag of “unique & surprising” to go and the barista shared a small cup of its cold brew for me to taste. I am glad i have tried because it was really surprised by its freshness and flavor and almost wanted to have another large cup of coffee if it’s not my first drink at that day of arrival after a 5 hr flight without a full meal😿
I followed the brew guide on the website but have cut half of the size and still get the same profile as I have had for cold brew.
I will definitely come back for other coffee drinks next time🙌
Nice staff with the chill atmosphere and a kids area provided which is rarely seen

text.text:
One of my favorite finding in Melrose and have seen myself coming back multiple times despite plenty other options around the area. It's also uncountable how many times I've recommended it to others.

The location's strategic being at the heart of the city, though it may mean parking can sometimes be tricky. For those with lil' kids, they do provide a nice play room so you can enjoy a bit of chillin time over great cup of joe.

I do love the contemporary atmosphere it features with the artsy paintings and posters around the walls.

The baristas are all very helpful in assisting you to pick your order and even accommodate customization requests.

On my initial visit, I went for their signature Vivid Cream Latte, which was their version of brown sugar latte with cream top and cocoa powder. The drink that made me fell in love with this place on first try, served just at right sweetness with great brown sugar taste that nicely didn't overpower the bold coffee flavor. The cream top also came as perfect balance to the cup, which sometimes atypical one ended up diluting the coffee.

On my other visits when I wasn't really feeling like having cream top coffee, I would go for their hot brown sugar latte introduced by the barista as I wanted brown sugar in my coffee but not the cream. I ended up easily being its loyalist!

text.text:
Such a cute coffee spot! I instantly loved both the exterior and interior—the place has so much charm and character. It’s the kind of spot that just feels good to be in.

The cozy vibe paired with the friendly and welcoming staff made the experience even better. Everyone was super kind and helpful, which made my visit feel extra special.

I ordered the Ultralight Bean, a caramel latte with cold foam, and it was absolutely delicious. The flavor was perfectly balanced—not overly sweet, just smooth and satisfying. I was super impressed with the quality and care put into the drink.

Can’t wait to come back and try more of their coffee and tea options. This place is definitely a new favorite!

Let me know if you’d like a shorter or more casual version too!

text.text: 5 stars around for this wonderful restaurant. The interior is wonderful, but the view on the Old Stone Church at Mission San Juan Capistrano is priceless. We sat in the area that is sunken under the sidewalk, with wide open windows looking on the ruins of the church. The food was outstanding. We had a lovely strawberry caprese salad and the bourbon duck liver pate plate for appetizers. I had the chef special shrimp ravioli in a lovely lemon cream sauce with heirloom tomatoes. My parents both got the bacon wrapped meatloaf. Perhaps the best highlight, though, was the service. I want to give a shout-out to our server, Clerisa. I was at the restaurant with my parents (both in their mid-80s). Clerisa (as were the rest of the attentive staff) was wonderful the entire time, but the tip of the cap goes to her graciously giving us an incredible desert (on the house). It was amazing ice cream (I'm guessing from McConnell's), topped with lovely chocolate cookie crumbs, caramel, and a mint leaf. Again, 5 stars around!

We have been a fan of Iron Wood  in our neighborhood then Sapphire with the new ownership but didn't realize The Bloom is also one of them. Any way we went out lastnight and had a great time. My salmon was cooked perfectly, supper hot with a thin layer of crispiness without being dry, moist and flavored. The succotash was just right. I didn't taste other dishes from my hubby and friends so cant tell but they finished their plates and enjoyed them. However, i did get to taste a fried zucchini blossom was very good, and the crispy brussel sprouts with pork belly was delicious. Our waitress and service were great.

Keep up the quality and creativities!🙏

text.text:
We went here this last Friday for my dad's birthday dinner. We sat in a large booth for six people, which created a really nice, intimate vibe. They also have really large windows, which invites an indoor, outdoor feel. Our server, Daren, was super attentive, nice, and eligible. We ordered that liver pate, focaccia bread, and ricotta gnocchi for starters. If you love pasta and pork belly, I highly recommend the ricotta gnocchi. I could have ordered this for my main dish!
Unfortunately, I didn't love my main dish, I ordered the bacon wrapped meatloaf, I just felt like the meatloaf was a little dry. But it came side of truffle Mac and cheese, which was perfectly flavored and not overly cheesy.  I also tried my boyfriend's rib eye which we both loved.
We also had a cake for my dad in the back which they brought out and lit candles, they also had their own little dessert ice cream they gave us. Overall had a great time. This place is also located in a fun area, right across the mission, and next to a few dive bars. Also across the street from the train tracks if you want to walk around for a glass of wine, dessert or something more casual after.

text.text:
Clean store and great selection, but the cashier rang up our items and double scanned an item, we didn't realize this until we were already back home. I called the store to inform them of the issue and asked for a refund, was told that the manager will need to review the footage to verify. Manager verified that the item was scanned too many times and a refund is warranted, but now I have to drive back to the store for the refund, which is an hour round trip for myself, first world problem I know, but could have been avoided if not for their cashier's mistake.

After looking at other reviews, I think it's important to mention that the cashier was Alissa D., past reviews also mention them by name so management may want to talk to this employee

text.text: I was the head bakerr for Bristol farms. Despite how they felt about me when I left the department they couldn't produce food for almost a month. I was the department and so I will tell you my secrets. I was locked inside the major freezer in the bakery department and when I told Joey the general manager about the faulty of equipment he told me I needed to be nicer. What does that even mean? My manager were Kiki and Madison, they refused to do their own work so I did inventory along with pulling for it the spoils, along for breaking down the pallet. I would usually find their breakfast on top of cakes that would then be served to you. There have been multiple times I had to pick out beans and rice from a vanilla cake because they put their breakfast burrito on the shelf above and the remnants fell on the to the cake below. They serve it, anyways. I can't tell you how many times I've had to tell them that nuts don't go on every sheet pan and if you have a sheet pan with no nuts, you need to wash it first. Kiki told me that nut allergies were make-believe. They do not wash their hands when they walk back into the kitchen. The cake decorator yatezti, didn't believe and refrigerating any of the cream that goes on top of the cake. There have been multiple days that I had picked out chunks of mold because they like to use the cream cheese that has been sitting on the bottom end of the cake counter. Sitting dark moist environments. I told her multiple times to let me know what she needed and I can assist her with the cream cheese. But she told me she didn't need to refrigerate the cream cheese. She told me that she just mixes it together and it makes a good consistency. What she's mixing in with the cream cheese is mold. I told Joey this the general manager at Bristol farms and he told me it was okay. I've since left Bristol farms and have continued on with my life but I can't keep thinking about everyone

text.text:
My recent trips to the Calabasas Bristol Farms have been consistently disappointing, proving that high prices certainly do not equate to high quality or service. This store demands a premium but delivers a decidedly subpar experience, particularly when compared to other local options.

The customer service at the specialty counters is scarce and, frankly, indifferent. Finding an employee to assist is a quest, and when you do, the service is minimal. This lack of attention is baffling given the store's purported high-end positioning.

More critically, the value scales here are completely off. The prices are exorbitant across the board, and the quality of the produce is simply not good enough to justify them. When Trader Joe's down the street offers noticeably fresher produce for literally a third of the price, it’s impossible to rationalize shopping here. It feels less like a market and more like a selling overpriced goods with attitude.

The checkout process is where the dysfunction climaxes. Typically, only one human cashier is open, leading to unnecessary long waits. The self-checkout stations, which should provide some speed, are an absolute disaster. They are overly sensitive, frequently "freaking out" with the slightest movement, and seem to be running on outdated, unreliable software. It's a system designed to frustrate customers rather than streamline purchases.

Bristol Farms needs to seriously invest in its operations: either update those temperamental self-checkout stations with working, modern software, or, preferably, hire more cashiers to provide the level of service customers paying these prices deserve. As things stand, this location is simply not worth the time or the cost, much like the "village" of Calabasas itself.

text.text:
BRISTOL FARMS is a luxurious grocery store selling an extensive selection of high quality consumables, alcoholic beverages, and sundries. Long isles display packaged goods; separate departments include prime meats, fish, poultry, fruits and vegetables.  The selection of alcoholic beverages is impressive. Their selection of vegan and gluten free foods is sizable.

As you would expect, the service is excellent. There are employees, throughout the store, who will accompany you when you're looking for an item. In a store this large and deeply stocked that's a major advantage.

STUFF: Prices are moderate to high. On Tuesdays, seniors receive a 10% discount off their entire order. Parking is free and easy. Everything's ADA compatible.

text.text: I visited Bristol Farms Woodland Hills for the first time last week, and I was very impressed by their selection and quality of products. They have a friendly and helpful staff, a clean and organized store, and a variety of specialty foods and beverages to choose from. I especially enjoyed their salad bar happy hour, where I got a delicious and fresh salad for a great price. They also have a hot food bar with different cuisines, a bakery with mouth-watering pastries, and a sushi department with authentic and tasty sushi. I also noticed that they have a wine, beer, and spirits section, as well as a coffee, juice, and smoothie bar. I will definitely come back to try more of their offerings and to buy some of their gourmet and organic groceries. Bristol Farms Woodland Hills is a gem in the neighborhood, and I highly recommend it to anyone looking for a high-quality and satisfying shopping experience..

text.text:
Bristol Farms in Newport Beach offers a premium grocery shopping experience that blends quality, variety, and an upscale atmosphere. From the moment you walk in, the store impresses with its clean, well-organized layout and inviting displays. The produce section is especially notable—everything is fresh, vibrant, and beautifully arranged, with a strong selection of organic and locally sourced items.

The meat and seafood counters are staffed by knowledgeable, friendly butchers who are happy to offer cooking tips or custom cuts. Their prepared foods section is a standout, offering gourmet options that rival restaurant fare—perfect for a quick lunch or an effortless dinner. The bakery and cheese sections are equally impressive, with artisanal breads, pastries, and an extensive range of international cheeses.

Bristol Farms also shines in its curated selection of wines, craft beers, and specialty products you won’t find in typical supermarkets. Prices are on the higher side, but the quality justifies the premium, especially for foodies or those hosting special gatherings.

Customer service is consistently attentive and polite, adding to the overall upscale experience. Whether you’re shopping for a dinner party or just grabbing a smoothie at the café, Bristol Farms in Newport Beach delivers a refined and satisfying visit.

text.text:
First time in Bristol Farms, I was returning home from L.A. and I was so hungry,
I saw the sushi counter, and was apprehensive. I looked closer and thought, this looks like real Japanese sushi!  So I bought 3 large trays. FYI I am half Japanese and I’ve been eating sushi since I was a tot.
This sushi is by far the best sushi I have ever found in any market, it was not buried in all that sugary, syrupy sauce with crunchy stuff smothering it, although you can order that way if you choose. No over cooked gummy rice, and a good balance of fish with some rice, not a glob of gummy rice with some fish. Included is a packet of wasabi, soy sauce was not included, but I’m sure available at the counter.
The quality of the fish was very good, melt in the mouth tender.  I think if you have to bury the sushi in all that garbage, how good is the fish? I know thats the westernization of sushi … yuk.
I learned from the cashier, the sushi chef/owner is Japanese and takes a lot of pride in his product. Well the proof is in the sushi! I highly recommend Bristol Farms sushi counter.

text.text:
I had an extremely upsetting experience at Bristol Farms that I feel the public should be aware of. While shopping, I was approached and accused of stealing shrimp — something I absolutely did not do. This accusation was made without any valid reason or evidence, and I could not help but feel I was being racially profiled. I used the self checkout to purchase chicken livers for my dogs food and some milk. I knew exactly who was attempting to purchase shrimp, it was a clean shaven white man with a polo shirt next to me.

The way the situation was handled made it even worse. The manager was dismissive, showed no real accountability, and made no effort to sincerely apologize or investigate the situation properly. Instead of addressing the harm caused, they treated me as if my feelings and dignity didn’t matter. His name is Brad. After letting Brad know I was getting profiled, he let me know that the register doesn’t see race. Well obviously I know that, but getting chased outside the store and assuming I was the one stealing, your staff see that.

Being profiled and falsely accused is humiliating and unacceptable, especially in a store that claims to value its customers. This incident has left me shaken, and I will not be returning to this location. I hope Bristol Farms takes this feedback seriously and invests in training their staff on bias awareness, customer respect, and accountability.

I’m also a chef that does pop up’s and work with community organizations so I will be letting everyone know of this harmful incident.

text.text:
Nestled behind Lincoln Blvd. in Westchester, a culinary experience awaits. Bristol Farms offers a megastore of healthy treats surrounded by a wide selection of upscale luxury items that comfort the soul.
An incredible deli with a hot bar on par with the finest of restaurants offers delicious chicken salad, wraps and gourmet meals. You can dine in a cozy cafe or enjoy the food at home.
The bakery offers fresh breads, incredible scones and sweet delicacies that would tempt any palette. Just when you think you have seen it all, a fresh meat section, sushi bar and a wide selection of healthy delicacies line the shelves. The healthfood megastore also offers vintage wines from all over the world and a extensive gourmet cheese selection.
Bristol Farms has a long history of delivering incredible food with the finest ingredients. They set the precedent for gourmet groceries with exquisite style and impeccable customer service.

text.text:
Cactus Blossom Collective is an absolute treasure in Livingston, Montana! This beautifully curated shop is more than just a boutique—it's a celebration of local talent and creativity. From handcrafted jewelry and artisan home goods to thoughtfully sourced apothecary items, every piece tells a story and supports independent makers.

The atmosphere is warm and inviting, making it a joy to browse. I especially love that they highlight local artists and creators, giving the space a truly authentic and community-driven feel. Whether you’re looking for a unique gift, a piece of Montana-made decor, or just want to soak in the inspiring ambiance, this shop is a must-visit.

Their commitment to sustainability and small businesses is evident in every product they carry. Plus, the events they host add an extra layer of charm, making it a hub for creativity and connection.

Highly recommend stopping by—this place is a true reflection of the heart and soul of Livingston!  Make sure to ask for Kristi—she’s wonderful and can help you find exactly what you are looking for.

text.text:
I secretly slipped in the other day. I’ve been avoiding my beloved cinnamon pastries here thanks to lackluster service, but against my better judgment I got one. Even though I know I can get them at a slightly higher price a few blocks to the east lol. Best of all - with a smile.

The lines are long here often. With good reason, but there are some flaws.

Previous review: MOMENTOUS OCCASION! Alas, finally I got a genuine, warm smile here! One of the guys that work in the little room where they prepare stuff. A baker? He was dressed like one. Anyway amazing! He should train (or reprogram) everyone else here! He’s actually not bad looking.

This used to be a five star review. The bread is top notch but the service is absolutely not.

Previous review: Please reprogram the staff. Yes, reprogram because everyone else here is an automaton struggling with their interactions in the most cosmopolitan city in earth. In front they have one highly efficient staff that makes things function, an always clueless, slothlike and socially inexperienced cashier and a barista that is ponderous and expressionless.

They’re probably all imported from Montana or Nebraska. Who knows? Devoid of much human contact or far worse. Cultural tipping points anyone? Nah, please don’t let it be so!

Today the cashier didn’t get the order right and renamed me. I kind of noticed something was off but didn’t find out till the barista only made one latte when I had asked for two. He asked me if the latte was mine instead of calling out a name and that’s when I saw I had a brand new name. lol. Instead of clarifying my name, which would involve more human interaction , the poor young woman went deeper into her introverted  comfort zone and wished everything would turn out fine. It didn’t though.

I have a theory about this place. Their programming limits them to smile expressly for weird and entitled Larchmont entertainment industry types. They actually live around here. lol.

Annoying anecdote of the year: the cashier renamed me with the name of a horrid supervisor I had to endure for a year and a half in the world’s most toxic job environment.  Actually this was kind of funny n a masochistic and self deprecating way. lol

They took soooooooo long sorting things out, etc that a meter maid was gleefully writing a ticket for me outside lol. Ok this is my fault but I’m warning everyone that you should never ever make the mistake of thinking a visit to Clark St can ever, ever be a quick one. lol pay your meter! lol.

Here is my first review:

We arrived at around 8 am and there was already a small line. We had to wait outside. There were a bunch of people sitting outside. They’ve got some pretty cool merch. They play cool enough music. Today it was Killers sounding alt pop.

There are literally a ton of pastry and bread options.

So my favorite bakery ever is in Berlin and this one comes very close but they don’t have the raspberry and white chocolate bread I had in Berlin. I mention the Berlin bakery because I haven’t run into a bakery quite like this one or Clark St in Los Angeles. Not to say we don’t have great bakeries here.

I had a breakfast plate with a pastry and a latte today. I ordered the Bacon and Eggs plate which included slices of bread, two scrambled eggs, three pieces of bacon, butter and preserves. The bread was incredibly fresh and the crusts weren’t too hard. They were just right. The bacon was cooked to perfection. It was not too thin and not too thick. The eggs were great.

I chose a Swedish cinnamon bun. It was amazing. I love cinnamon bread. The pastry was soft inside and had a slightly crunchy exterior. It paired well with my three shot latte which was incredibly balanced and subtle in flavor.

I tried a croissant which was great but it isn’t the best croissant in Los Angeles. It’s close though.

When we were leaving it was close to 9 am and it got pretty busy.

Nice clean private bathroom with a baby shelf.

Meter parking in front.

text.text:
As a matcha drinker, I was highly disappointed at their “matcha” drink on the menu. Very poor excuse to call it matcha when it tastes like a one dimensional vanilla creamer. You could close your eyes to compare the two and believe it was just that. Would it be hard to just… add more matcha?

Also, $14 for bacon and eggs? Seriously? This place isn’t even a restaurant… It’s $15 just to grab a whole pack of pasture raised eggs & bacon at the store. Save your money, this is just another overpriced hipster bakery that leaves their baked goods baking in their glass window. On top of that, the workers here were unfriendly and seemingly unhappy to greet people.

text.text:
I recently visited this charming cafe, and it was a delightful experience. The interior is warm and welcoming. Cozy nooks, thoughtful decor, and soft lighting or get some work done while enjoying good food and drinks.

I ordered an Iced Latte, which was smooth, creamy, and just the right balance of rich espresso and milk. It was refreshing and satisfying, exactly what I needed to recharge. Alongside, I had a Ham and Cheese Croissant—flaky, buttery, and filled with just the right amount of melted cheese and ham. It was delicious, perfectly toasted, and complemented the latte beautifully.

This cafe’s inviting atmosphere and high-quality offerings make it a place I’d love to return to. It’s perfect for a solo visit or to catch up with friends, with a vibe that feels both trendy and cozy. Highly recommended for anyone looking for a spot with personality and warmth!

text.text:
I can see why some people are excited about this place! It’s definitely clean, the staff is super friendly, and they have some really unique preserves and spreads. However, I personally found it lacking in a few areas. I tried the biscuit sandwich with pimento cheese, and while it was decent, it didn’t quite live up to the nearly $8 price tag for me. The NOLA coffee was another story; it had a bit of a gritty taste, which was surprising and not the best experience.

On a high note, if you happen to find the Big Debra oatmeal cream pie, definitely give it a try! It’s delightful—spicy, creamy, and sweet all at once. I really loved it, and I think it’s worth the almost $7. Overall, while I appreciate the unique offerings, I believe there might be some better choices out there for the price.

text.text:
Cookbook Market is one of those rare spots that feels like it was curated by someone who not only understands food, but reveres it. It’s got more deliciousness per square inch than any market I’ve ever seen—every item feels hand-picked for maximum quality and flavor. You won’t find massive inventory here, but what you will find is impeccable produce, thoughtfully sourced pantry staples, and high-end ingredients that make you want to cook even if you weren’t planning to.

It leans more Erewhon than Vons when it comes to pricing, but that’s part of the point—you’re paying for a curated experience, supporting local producers, and stepping into a small space that feels like a love letter to seasonal cooking. The breads are excellent, the cheese selection is small but mighty, and even the olive oil feels like it comes with a story.

Love the neighborhood vibe too—it’s a place where you overhear conversations about dinner parties, food writing, and which tomato is best for your sauce. Always worth the stop. Five stars.

text.text: Cookbook never disappoints, in a city always seen as erewhon city. I have to say that I’m really not an erewhon person anymore after so many bad experiences. Cookbook recipes and products are for me, a French person living in LA, just a one way ticket to paris. Their premade salads are amazing and made with fresh products. Same goes for their pies and pâtisseries and viennoiseries. I love their rye brownie. Maybe the best brownie ever!? Everyone working there for the most part is very passionate about food and cuisine. We had a Cesar salad, a chicken paillard, which could have been a bit more generous same for the salad as we expected it to be topped with anchovies, the potatoes were delicious and fresh, same for the soup, topped with pesto. I recommend this place 100% and will definitely go back. Hopefully they can solve the complicated parking situation.

text.text:
Blink once and you might miss this place. It's on the corner of an office building on a residential street. But don't miss out on this if you're looking for a serious coffee shop in Ktown, and not one of those "coffee" places that has drinks that are more instagrammable than drinkable. Don't get me wrong, i enjoy them once in a while, but if you're a coffee afficionado, this is the place.

Their latte is good, a bit on the hotter side but that the foam stayed thick and creamy. The cortado though was more of a macchiato, still good. Bummer they don't have coffee cups for inside, just to go cups.

Loved the minimalist interior accented by the gallery wall of people. It almost feels like an art gallery with a coffee shop instead of the other way round.

text.text:
FattyMart is an interesting concept, a mashup of Eataly-style market meets Taiwanese food court, with a sprinkle of general Asian grocery items. The vibe is young and energetic, with a few tables outside the market and casual seating scattered throughout the space.

We ordered the Fatty Folds with three-cup chicken, wagyu beef pho banh mi, and beef bulgogi bowl with a fatty add-on. The Fatty Folds were an interesting twist on the Taiwanese scallion pancake, used as taco-style to wrap your choice of protein. While the concept was fun, the pancake itself was overly greasy and lacked scallion flavor. It’s a pass.

The wagyu banh mi was good overall, though a bit dry on its own. Thankfully, the pho beef dip was excellent and really made the dish better.

The bulgogi bowl came with only six tiny slices of beef on a full bowl of rice. Without the fatty add-on ($4), it would’ve been disappointing. Big thanks to the waitress who strongly recommended upgrading.

Service was quick, and the staff were friendly and helpful. I’d give the food 3.5 out of 5 stars, and the staff and setting 4 out of 5. Overall, it’s a 4-star place, worth checking out for the concept for once.

text.text:
Arrived on Thursday night at just before 7:30 PM. Asked some questions about the menu and ordered the BBQ pork bowl and Beef Bulgogi bowl. Both we served to us parts of meat were warm other parts less than room temperature. Rice at or near room temperature. Luck would have it they have a microwave for customer use. Honestly the bowls were just ok at best.

A person sat down next to us after ordering and their food came out and they were told the restaurant was about to close and they would need to leave. We found this odd given it wasn't even 8pm which we later learned is when they close. One by one tables were being told that they needed to leave. Then came out turn, young man who took our order came and said we needed to leave even though we were still eating and had beers half full. He told us he would give us paper cups for our beers. I'm very sure this restaurant doesn't have a license to sell draft beer to go as that doesn't exist in Los Angeles. We finished our beers in less than 5 minutes from when told to leave and during that time staff stacked all the tables and chairs around us.

Very odd experience to say the least. We really wanted this to be good, but it wasn't. We eat out in the area often and will choose other places.

text.text:
Flouring Cake Shop – A Beautiful Dessert Destination in Chinatown LA

I’ve visited Flouring Cake Shop several times, and each experience has been consistently wonderful. The shop itself is charming, decorated in soft purple tones, with a clean and modern feel. Staff are always polite, welcoming, and knowledgeable about their products, which makes the experience even more enjoyable.

The cakes here are truly special. They are elegantly decorated—often adorned with edible flowers and artistic details—making them perfect for both everyday treats and special occasions. The texture is slightly lighter than many traditional American-style cakes. The buttercream is smooth, not overly sweet, and balances beautifully with the cake. While it is not an Asian-style cake (not rubbery or overly moist), when eaten at the right temperature and on the same day, it has just the right balance of softness without dryness.

Flouring offers both individual sheet cake slices and full custom tiered cakes for events. Their flavors are creative and well-executed, including passion fruit, lavender lemon, black sesame, strawberry, and seasonal specials. Beyond cakes, they also serve unique desserts like Pavlova with yuzu, buttery shortbread cookies, and scones with oats—something between a traditional scone and an oatmeal cookie, deliciously balanced and not too dense or dry.

The price is big for a small piece but I have to say their cake is fancy, beautiful & delicious. It is worth it.

Overall, Flouring Cake Shop is a gem in Chinatown LA. Whether you’re looking for a beautifully decorated whole cake for a celebration or simply want to enjoy a refined dessert with unique flavors, this shop is well worth a visit.

Street parking only
There is Metro Station Nearby

All goodies are tasty!

text.text:
🌟🌟🌟🌟🌟
I Hate Cake—But This One Changed My Mind

I’ve spent years dodging birthday slices, declining dessert menus, and side-eyeing frosting like it owed me money. Not even as a kid did I like cake. Cake and I? Not friends. Everything i got to try was great, but then came this ube and coconut cake and OMG!!!!

It didn’t just taste good—it rewrote my dessert beliefs. Moist without being mushy, sweet without the sugar assault, and layered like a symphony. The texture? A velvet rebellion. The flavor? A sermon in indulgence. I didn’t just eat it—Im forever converted. Thank you!!

text.text:
I cannot _believe_ it's taken me this long to review Flouring LA! Hands down one of the cutest bakeries of all time and 10 out of 10 delicious! Amaaazing flavor combinations that change seasonally, the owner is a Chinese-Latina LA native with amazing taste! Her most popular flavors are the black sesame cake slices and Ube. All her baked goods pair extremely well with the coffee you can get next door and I love the shortbread cookies with the coffee. My partner and I have visited a handful of times so our tips are: get there early because they sell out, parking is usually street, grab a coffee from next door and order 3-6 cake slices and cookies to split and take home.
Its great for couples or pairs on a lazy weekend and you can migrate over to Chinatown when your done eating to pickup some $5 pants lol

text.text:
This place is busy and parking can be a little tough.  As soon as you walk in, you are warmly greeted.  It gets busy, but the line moves fast.  They had so many items to purchase besides coffee. It was hard to focus.  They had cute mugs, a variety of coffees, and so much more.
As soon as it was my turn to order,  Annie (owner) was super friendly and took the time to help me choose pastries to eat and coffee beans to take back home to my parents.  Annie explained how she loves doing coffee collabs and she's owned and operated this place for 10 years.  The way she explains products and talks to customers, you can just tell by the vibe that she loves what she does.

I ordered:

1.  Iced ceramonial matcha latte:  This was a nice comforting drink.  It wasn't overly strong, matcha, and you can taste the hint of honey.  The perfect drink while I stand in line outside for Gooey Center Cinnamon rolls.

2.  Nutella croissant:  Messy delightful treat, with nutella throughout

3.  Strawberries and cream:  I wasn't a fan of this one.   It was a little too tart for me.   I didn't get much sweetness from the cream.

4.  Mini donut holes w/ vanilla cream filling:  This would have been tasty without the filling.  It tasted like cream cheese and kind of threw the flavor off

They had a cool colab going on with Gooey Center, cinnamon rolls, and Hap's Burgers.   You can get coffee, breakfast sandwiches, and cinnamon rolls in one place.   It's like a one-stop shop.   It's super convenient for the shopper like me.   I was able to try all 3 places while waiting for Gooey  Center to set up and open up.

Highly recommend coming by and checking out.  Annie is super nice.   She made me feel welcome and even introduced me to some of her customers. She had shown me where to line up for Gooey Center and spoke of Hap's Burgers.  Hap's burger is there on Wednesday and Saturday.  Gooey Center pops up there on Saturdays sometimes.  You'll have to check the website and see where they are for the week.

text.text:
The good: amazing pastries, helpful staff
The bad: no indoor seating at all, completely barren walls, no music or ambiance; seems designed to get you to leave as soon as possible

Granted, F&F has giant shoes to fill, as this space was formerly occupied by Silverlake Coffee, a cozy community hub with big leather couches, comfy chairs and lots of tables, local artists’ work on the walls, and great music curated on the fly by the baristas. I came to check out the new business and to hopefully get some computer work done, but the vibe was so stark and unchill that I got a (quite excellent) quiche and left.

If this place a) added comfy indoor seating, b) played some tunes, and c) lowered the lights and ditched the minimalist “trendy Hollywood” vibe it would be an easy 5 stars. Great location and great food — but just not an inviting space.

This revival store offers a mini mart where you can buy a few different type of groceries as well as bread, pastries and coffee. You can enjoy them on the outdoor terrace that face the old factory, now a huge decoration store.

text.text:
Howdy Bagel is a total treasure in Tacoma every sandwich is thoughtfully crafted and full of bold, beautiful flavor.

The English Breakfast is crisp and refreshing, layered with cucumbers and onions that brighten every bite. It’s like morning sunshine in bagel form. The Sausage & Egg hits all the savory notes you crave comforting, hearty, and so satisfying. And the Avocado Boast is a fresh, creamy dream for anyone who loves avocados.

There are so many ways to build your perfect bagel here, and every one of them fills your belly and your soul. Whether it’s your first visit or your fiftieth, you’ll leave smiling and already planning your return.

Run, don’t walk. Your bagel bliss awaits.

text.text:
This bagel shop has the best bagels I have ever had. The Grit City Lox is absolutely amazing. I LOVE that they have a hot smoked salmon option, as I don't like cold smoked Salmon. The pickled onions and cabbage on this are to die for. There is so much flavor in every single bite.

The Bacon, Egg and Cheese is also amazing. They have a howdy sauce on it, and it is so flavorful and has a little kick to it. The Rosemary Seasalt Bagel is my favorite, it has the perfect amount of flavor to it.

Everything here is absolutely amazing, it is well worth the line. It does usually have a line though, so just be prepared that it's not a quick stop. I do wish that they'd add an online ordering system to it, but man oh man it's delicious.

Also, this business is just absolutely amazing, please go and support them.

text.text:
Finally got the chance to try howdy bagels! Honestly so worth the hype, we got the rosemary salt bagels and it was one of the best I’ve ever had. Crunchy and soft with the perfect amount of salt (for salt lovers). There absolutely will be quite a long line so be prepared. The indoor is decorated in a perfect western/hipster theme. Prices are fairly typical. We got the sausage egg and cheese add ago and it had a delicious aioli on it. We also did the avo boast which was great for vegetarians! Iced vanilla latte was surprisingly good but quite small for a medium. I’ll definitely be back when I’m in town!
Be warned: there is very little seating inside, only a few tables which were completely full with their own lines by opening.

text.text:
Joan’s on Third has the best Chinese chicken salad! I’ve ordered their short rib sandwich too- which is also delicious. I’ve never been to one in person, but this weekend I ventured my way here. I was surprised to see they had breakfast options! Although we didn’t order it, their corned beef hash looked amazing. They also have so many goodies. It was like Disneyland inside. They had ice cream, a dessert area, snacks, candies, and food options in the cases like quiches, lasagna, meatballs…

They have open seating. It was crowded on a Saturday but the service was great and the food came out quick and hot. Definitely need to check this place out if you’re in the area and want a delicious bite to eat!

text.text:
I used to love coming here. It felt like a staple in my L.A. routine. But a few things have slipped, and it feels like they haven’t evolved with what diners expect today.

The food is good and tasty. It’s the kind of place you go because you know exactly what you’ll like. The ambiance still carries that laid-back, market-meets-cafe charm.

They don’t offer gluten-free bread for sandwiches. That’s a big miss for people with dietary needs or preferences. It feels like a small thing, but in 2025, it matters.

Portion sizes are good, but the price is high. You’re paying for the reputation and the location, not always for innovation.

Service is friendly, but not always efficient. During busy times, orders seem slower, the staff is juggling too much, and things can lag.

Verdict:
Joan’s On Third is still worth a visit if you love the familiar flavors and the comfy, local feel. Just go in with tempered expectations. It has charm, but it’s not keeping pace with what diners expect now.

text.text:
So unique, so amazing!

I came to Joan’s for lunch, after hearing great things about their new burgers.

After looking through their sit down menu, we tried out their lunch selection, which was delicious. My chili dog was much larger than expected, and was an amazing blend of rich brioche bread, tender sausage, and savory chili. As for the burger, the beef was great quality! Their pickles are made in-house, as well as their house sauce, which was evident in their fresh, unique taste. However, if there is one thing you order, try the delicious onion strings. They are so crispy, perfectly battered, and sweetly onion flavored. Definitely a slept on treat.

I was highly impressed by the sheer variety of items available at this location. From grab-and-go deli items, to wines, to desserts and sweets, to restaurant-style hot meals, there is something for everyone!

Joan, the owner, is incredibly friendly. She talked to us about the menu, and even recommended some of her favorites. It’s truly refreshing to see a business owner so invested in their product. In fact, the entire staff was outstandingly kind, especially the kitchen crew, which deserves all the recognition!

Highly recommend! 😼

text.text:
OVERALL:  Would love to go back to try more of their items!

Family friendly:  Yes and no… No restriction on age but they have a sign that limits 5 customers at a time in their store
Pet friendly: No
Parking: Street Parking

FOOD/MENU:
Mango Sticky Rice Rice Crispy Treat (Coconut infused marshmallow, dried mango, toasted coconut) $5: 4 Stars – At first bite, you really did not taste anything… like it tasted like a normal rice crispy treat… but slowly, the coconut and mango flavor come in and its like WOW.

Black sesame rice crispy treat (brown butter, roasted black sesame seeds, black sesame paste, flaky sea salt) $5: 3 Stars – I really wanted to love this since all things black sesame is amazing!!! The flavor was light, very light… If it was more robust flavor, I think it would have been a lot better.

Vegan Ube cookies & cream rice crispy treat (ube marshmallows, vegan butter, gluten free oreo pieces) $5: 3 Stars – I’m on the fence about this.  This was opposite for me with the Ube and Mango… I could taste it right away but the more I ate, the less I liked it… nothing bad about it but maybe a little artificial tasting?

Classic Chocolate Chip Cookie (milk and dark chocolate and Okinawan sea salt) $5: 4 Stars – This was soooo yummy and gooey.  I loved that they used large chucks verse “chips.”  I do wish this was a little bigger for being priced at $5.  I’ve seen other bakeries that have smaller cookies but priced 2-3x more and are horrible… so I guess I shouldn’t complain? LOL

Yuzu-berry tiramisu (ladyfinger sponge, yuzu soak, marionberry jam, vanilla mascarpone cream) $12: 3 Stars – Very yuzy, very berry tasting LOL I do prefer the classic tiramisu over this one though… I think this is the time that classic will trump modern/contemporary 😊

RESTAURANT/SERVICE:
Small little cute bake shop.  Due to the limit of 5 customers inside, we did not stay long as a small line started to form by the time we were done ordering.  Even with the limited amount of time spent, the workers were extremely friendly and helpful.

text.text:
Kindness & Mischief Coffee is a nice spot in the heart of Highland Park! The vibe here is effortlessly cool, with a cozy, artsy atmosphere that makes it the perfect spot to relax or catch up with friends. The coffee was good—I highly recommend their almond milk mocha, which was creamy and perfectly balanced.

The staff is friendly and welcoming, which adds to the overall charm of the place. I love the little touches, like the quirky artwork and the thoughtful details in their presentation. It’s clear that a lot of care goes into everything they do.

It can get pretty crowded, especially on weekends, and seating can be a bit tight. But honestly, that’s just a testament to how popular this place is! If you’re in the area, Kindness & Mischief is definitely worth a visit. It’s a great spot to enjoy quality coffee and soak in the local Highland Park vibe.

text.text: I have been visiting Kindness and Mischief over the years, and every single time I feel so welcome. There is a joyful energy and a real spirit of creativity at play in this space. Highland Park has changed over many years from being an affordable low income area, to one that is become increasingly gentrified. Kindness and Mischief represents the spirit of pulling an idea together and building something amazing. Taking a chance on a space and an area to grow. Although I do not live in the Los Angeles area any longer, I will always push people to take a detour on their adventures and spend some time at this establishment.

text.text:
I wish I could give it 10 stars!
Culver city residents and all others, if you haven't been, you're missing a pleasant evening out. Kustaa is a inconspicuous little spot. You'll  pass by,  thinking it's a only a deli (you may be able to see the cheese display from the window).. but nooo.. they have a nice little surprise for you in the back. Stringed lights, couch seating and a nicely decorated eating patio awaits you.  For those who are in love with the charcuterie experience,  Kustaa is the place for you. Their platters are amazing and delicious. Manu, our sommelier was extremely personable and very knowledgeable. His french accent made us feel like we were in France.  His recommendation on wine was spot on! He put our wine in the coolest, little cooler bag to keep it chilled. Yon, the owner made a small oversight, but quickly made up for it with a platter of bread and dips (on the  house) The whole staff was very friendly. The woman who brought out our platter, named and thoroughly described all the meats and  cheeses that were on there. My friends ordered from the menu and enjoyed their meals. Make sure you give Kustaa a visit. Tell Manu, Gina's review brought you in.

Metered street parking.

text.text: I visited the garden today on May 17, very impressed by the similarities between this garden and the one in Suzhou, China. Flowers are blooming in this mid/late spring period, the Japanese cheese wood fragrance reminds me of home. I didn’t try the tea house, but that’s probably the best spot in the garden for enjoying Chinese tea. They have a couple of vendors in the garden, but I don’t know if they are regulars or not. They had Pacific Islanders performing today, also a cultural heritage learning session. Quite an active center for cultural sharing in the heart of town, close to both Union Station and the river bank, very central location and easily accessible by public transit.

text.text:
This Japanese market is a hidden goldmine if you’re into snacks, sushi, sweets, or just vibey Asian food finds without spending a bag.

The place is massive — rows on rows of goodies you didn’t even know existed. Definitely the go-to spot when you want something fun, fast, and fire without sitting down at a full-blown restaurant.

Came here to grab a poke bowl and some sweets — left with way more than I planned, and still spent way less than expected. Great bang for your buck if you’re ballin’ on a budget but still want quality.

There’s also a big parking garage (free with validation), and it’s connected to a whole mall full of cool shops, restaurants, and dessert spots. Kinda perfect if you wanna make a little day out of it.

Whether you’re hunting for rare snacks, drinks, or a quick sushi fix — this spot’s a sleeper hit. Highly recommend pulling up.

text.text:
My fiance and I found this gem from a YouTube show on Buzzfeed called Worth It (Episode was Wine Pairings) and added it to our list of places to visit during our anniversary vacation visiting from Las Vegas last week!
The moment we entered, we were greeted by the friendliest faces and it wasn't long before Devra made herself available to help us out. Since we were only visiting a day, she happily helped us gather a small but incredible assortment of cheeses and meats for our little AirBnB charcuterie board. We weren't expecting the level of customer service we experienced but goodness did Devra go above an try new d beyond, helping us try various new things from meat paté, Rose Jam, and some very fun cheeses!
We're adding this lovely place to our list of must vist every time we're back in the area and we'll certainly be bringing along friends and family to experience this amazing little shop.
Thank you again to Devra for helping make our 8 year anniversary so so special and memorable! We can't wait to visit again :)

text.text: I'll start off by saying my girlfriend and I ordered two sandwiches. The Normandie and the O.M. breakfast sandwich. The Normadie was very tasty while the O.M. Breakfast sandwich didn't really taste like much besides the sausage. Upon ordering, the cashier had no energy or welcoming attitude with a very monotone welcome. I don't really care about that, but I just wanted to add it because after ordering, I proceeded to ask if they can cut the sandwiches in half for us or if they're already cut. They said they're already cut in the most "leave" kind of voice. Then we waited a bit while walking around, hear our name called, picked up the order, and left. Whoever worked the bagging area was very nice and energetic though! When we left, I checked the food in the car and only one sandwich was cut in half, not the breakfast sandwich though. I didn't ask for much and it's so simple to answer a super easy question such as them being cut in half. I don't understand how it was miscommunicated. Although the Normandie was very good, the sauce was pretty much useless. It added no flavor to the sandwich, which is fine because it's already a good sandwich. The breakfast sandwich was very ok. The prices were very steep for what is served. The total for two sandwiches was $31 with no add-ons and the sizes were moderate with the breakfast sandwich being about the size of my palm and the Normandie being a little bigger than my hand.

text.text:
At this restaurant, you place your order at the counter and pay in advance, so it’s a good idea to have an idea of what you’d like before stepping up to order. The interior is fairly spacious with a nice sense of openness, making it comfortable to dine in without feeling crowded. Drinks such as water are self-serve, which adds to the casual atmosphere. Compared to a full-service restaurant, it feels much more approachable and easy to visit, even for someone dining alone.

The food itself was excellent flavorful, well-prepared, and served in portions that felt just right, not overly large. Since the cuisine is Chinese, it’s perfect for sharing with friends or family, allowing everyone to enjoy a variety of dishes together. During my visit, I tried several items including the mapo tofu, boiled dumplings, mixed noodles, and fried chicken. Every dish was delicious, full of flavor, and very satisfying.

There were also several types of rice to choose from, which made the meal feel customizable to personal taste. Although I wasn’t able to try dessert this time, the options looked very tempting, and I would love to save room for one on my next visit. The pricing felt quite reasonable given the quality and variety, making it a place I could easily see myself coming back to whenever I’m craving good Chinese food.

text.text:
Providore is one of Portland’s hidden gems — more than just a grocery store, it’s a full-on experience. I can spend time wandering through the aisles, discovering high quality produce and specialty ingredients that truly make cooking feel inspiring. Everyone who works there is warm and welcoming, which makes the visit even better.

With grocery prices being what they are these days, I’d rather spend on ingredients that actually last and taste good and Providore always delivers. I especially love grabbing their fresh pasta; it’s one of the rare spots where convenience doesn’t come at the cost of quality.

Our latest favorite? Their frozen chocolate chip cookies. Perfect for those random nights when all you want is something warm, gooey, and made with care…truly the best!

text.text:
If you find yourself searching for a breakfast spot that hits all the right notes, look no further than Provisions Market Hall. From the moment we placed our orders at the counter, the experience was seamless and satisfying. The freshness of the food was apparent with each bite. I indulged in a Croque Madame and Avocado Toast, both of which were a delightful fusion of classic taste and culinary craftsmanship.

Not to be overlooked, their baked goods are a sheer delight – each item more delectable than the last. It’s evident that Provisions Market Hall prides itself on the quality and taste of their offerings. With food brought right to your table and flavors that impress, this place is a gem waiting to be discovered. I encourage anyone to stop by. Chances are, you’ll leave as pleasantly surprised and content as I did.

text.text:
I Like Coffee Because It Gives Me The Illusion That I Might Be Good At Giving Reviews. That said let’s begin this roaster review.

Regent Coffee is a local coffee roaster that produce exceptional quality drinks. They are located on Brand ave in Glendale. They have coffee and tea drinks as well as specialties. Similarly, they offer a limited pastries.

Indoor seats are nonexistent albeit they have front outdoor seats with a fantastic street view. We came on a warm-98 degree-afternoon to quench our thirst. We were perfunctorily greeted by a tall female (with pink highlight hair) staff. I perused their menu and ordered a Burundi Cold Brew ($7.50) x 1/2 & 1/2 milk. I was desirous of having refreshing drink at this shop, and they did not disappoint. My CB was really smooth, full, and perfectly sweetened with slight hint of Mango fruit.

Prices matched the quality of their coffee drinks. Service was good. Staff were affable with compendious knowledge of coffee making. Vibe was positive.

Overall, as a first time customer I liked  my cold brew and had a pleasant order experience. I highly recommend you visit.

text.text: I had SUCH an incredible experience here & ended up saying yes to the dress—after visiting several other stores and getting worried I wouldn't find one I loved! Nicole was AMAZING to work with!!! She was so knowledgeable on each dress, the designer recommendations, and different ways you can style it (from veils to accessories to different bustle styles). The experience here was far superior than other stores—from when I first booked an appointment & chose my favorites in the portal, to the two appointments I had to lock down the dress. What I especially loved was that they weren't pushy at all in urging me to make a decision, and they took a million pictures of me in each dress in the store & natural lighting so I could sit with each one and decide over time. Candidly, before I booked, I wasn't sure if I wanted to pay for an appointment, so I was prioritizing spots with free appointments, but it was truly worth every penny. 1000% recommend going here!

text.text:
Beautiful space and great vibes, but the matcha latte was a big disappointment. It tasted mostly like milk with barely any matcha flavor. I was told it would cost another $3 for an extra shot—unreasonable, especially when other LA cafés offer strong matcha and are happy to adjust (and the matcha latte was already $9 by itself). For a spot in Larchmont, the quality just didn’t match the price or the expectations. (1/5 for the matcha.)

They also forgot my congee, but once I followed up, they brought it out—and it was fantastic. The mushroom congee was warm, flavorful, and comforting. I just wish it had more mushrooms. (4.5/5 for the congee.)

I’d come back for the food and atmosphere, but please, Suá—fix the matcha latte. It really brings down an otherwise wonderful experience.

text.text:
This coffee spot is a gem for anyone who loves unique, handcrafted drinks especially matcha lovers. The vibe inside is calm and modern.

We tried the Strawberry Pistachio Milk and the Strawberry Matcha, and both were delicious. They were perfectly balanced, not overly sweet, but still full of flavor. A nice touch was the freeze-dried strawberry slices on top, which added both a fun texture and a pop of flavor.

It did take a little longer than your average coffee shop, but it seems like they make each drink to order with nothing pre-batched. If you’re not in a rush, the wait is totally worth it for the quality and creativity.

text.text: I stopped by SUA and ordered the Honey Matcha Latte—definitely one of the best matcha drinks I’ve had in a while. The matcha was rich and smooth, with a fresh, slightly grassy note that wasn’t overpowering. The honey added a subtle sweetness that really elevated the drink. It’s clear that SUA puts thought into their flavor balance and quality. The presentation was beautiful too, and the overall vibe of the café is cozy and modern. A perfect spot for a chill afternoon break. I’ll be coming back for sure!

text.text:
Fun little market that opened up recently with a lot of interesting food and drinks.   They describe themselves as stocking "artisanal snacks" and I think that's really apt.   Think of it as fancy foods you'd put out for guests while hosting a book club or something.

It isn't a big shop but you will spend a lot of time browsing the shelves as you'll be reading a lot of descriptions of the products as many of them are unique.  The owner has added a few hand-written cards with additional information and gladly answers any questions.

I picked up a few items and they've all been very good.   Definitely recommend stopping by if you're in the neighborhood.

text.text:
This simple and elegant shop is a great place for foodies and for the people who love them.
The owner Sophie is incredibly kind and invested in the experience of those who shop here!

I was thrilled as I have been itching to find such a place with all of the thoughtfully curated tinned fishes, snacks, beverages, and (soon) CHEESE! Gorgeous glassware, flatware and fun food themed candles as well.

I left with some Fishwife tins, butter, snacks and a heart full of joy.

They only recently opened so they are still filling their inventory but if you are looking for something new, interesting or perhaps isn't easily found at Coop or Nugget Superette Market IS THE PLACE.

editorialSummary.text: Storied kitchenwares shop with a gourmet deli dispensing pro-level cooking tools & gadgets.

text.text:
I have an infinite love of gourmet markets and shops that stock items for my #culinaryadventures I have been coming to Surfas since they were located in Culver City.

This location is crammed tight with stuff to make your epicurean heart sing. From butters, cheeses, pastas, jams, olive oils, Asian food accompaniments, seasonings, gadgets, pots, pans, chocolates, nuts ETC. they have everything here. We went 2 weeks ago when they were have a HUGE sale and I got some loot for Birthdays coming up and Housewarming gifts for new neighbors.

If you are a die-hard foodie or you have to purchase a gift for one I highly recommend this spot. Parking can be tricky though (especially when they are busy) also the Cafe makes great sandwiches and the music in here is always inviting.

text.text:
My visit to Surfas Culinary District exceeded expectations! I came in for stainless steel pots and pans, leaving with much more. Besides restaurant supplies, they have a great food section with everything from olive oil to chocolates, paste, flour, meat, and sprinkles. I'm a sucker for in-store sampling, and I had the bread and butter--it was amazing! Who knew bread tasted so good? I also sampled Lebanon Honey, which was so delicious that I purchased a jar.
We had lunch and sat outside; it was sunny and relaxing. There is plenty of parking - and the customer service was exceptional. This place won't disappoint!"
Enjoy
Peace/Love
Be A Proud American

text.text: Wow, I wandered in on a local excursion (I wanted to see the house used for Six Feet Under, it’s just down the street) and saw this place. As a good writer and home cook/baker, I love a good kitchen supply store and Surfas was simply overwhelming in scope and product—so much for the professional food service and many items that are hard to find for bakers, cake makers, just so many tools. Not to mention an entire refrigerator case dedicated to butter. Came home with lots of fun ingredients and tools!

text.text:
This restaurant was amazing!!

The service was friendly and fast and the food was delicious. The portions here are huge -- we both had enough leftovers for lunch the next day! My boyfriend is Vietnamese, so we like to think we know our way around good Viet, and we both agreed this restaurant is delicious. We're already excited to come back and try more dishes!

Pro tip: come with friends so you can order a bunch of plates and share -- trust me, you'll want to taste everything. Parking can be a bit tricky in the area, so give yourself a little extra time to find a spot. Totally worth it, though!

text.text:
The Cakery is such a hidden gem!!

If you want some high quality desserts that is the right enough sweetness, you will absolutely love this place!

We tried everything from slices of their basque cheesecakes, madeleines, canneles, and financier and here were our favorites!

cheesecake: cookie and cream, strawberry and matcha
madeleine: salted caramel, earl grey
financier: snickers caramel
cannele: chocolate and matcha

You really can't go wrong with anything you order. They have a cafe opening up soon in Miramar where they'll serve the same treats alongside with some beverages that will pair well with your desserts. I'm pretty stoked for that to open!

text.text:
We visited this restaurant to celebrate our one year anniversary, and while there were some really lovely touches, the overall experience didn’t quite live up to the high expectations, especially given the price point.

On the positive side, the team customized our menus with a sweet anniversary message, gave us a beautiful window seat with a view, and never made us feel rushed. The service was decent, and the overall vibe was calm and upscale.

That said, for a bill that came out to over $700 for two people (with tip), I expected a higher level of attention to detail and execution. I ordered the surf and turf ($157) with my steak medium rare, but it came out medium well. I typically don’t send things back, but at that price, I wanted it done right. To the restaurant's credit, the waiter apologized, had a new steak prepared, and removed the lobster tail from the bill. Still, it left me feeling underwhelmed.

There were other small misses, like the yucca fries my partner and I ordered to share. They came out with truffle oil on them, despite us asking for it on the side. Not a huge deal in isolation, but again, for a high-end experience, I expected more care.

Maybe it’s my bias coming from the NYC area, where even mid-range restaurants often deliver a wow factor. While this place might be worth it for a one-time special occasion, I personally left disappointed and wouldn’t rush back.

I had the pleasure of dining at The Marine Room and was thoroughly impressed by the exemplary standard of service and cuisine.

From the outset, the staff demonstrated impeccable professionalism, offering attentive and courteous service. The atmosphere was refined and elegant, creating a perfect setting for a sophisticated dining experience.

The menu was thoughtfully crafted, showcasing exceptional ingredients and culinary creativity. Each course was presented with great attention to detail, and the flavors were memorable.

I would highly recommend it to those seeking exceptional cuisine, outstanding service, and an elegant setting.

text.text: My husband and I had a great time. We had made reservations for the Rising Tide Dinner and we got such a great table by a window. The view was absolutely gorgeous, skies were clear with wisps of clouds and we enjoyed seeing the sunset and the waves. Food was incredible, presented well and it was delicious. Three course meal was so good everything sounded great. We got the Crudo and Steak Tartare to start. 2nd course we got the Chicken with gnocchi and the Spotted Sea Bass. AMAZING. The desserts were so yummy...Strawberry Cheesecake and the S'mores were great. Had a couple drinks each: Sumac Sunset and Rum for the Hills and overall it was such a relaxing outing. Valet wasn't even that expensive $15, well worth it. Will be back for sure!

text.text: Every time I stop by The Mixing Glass, Gaby and her team teach me something new about a spirit or cocktail I’d never even heard of. They really care about everything they do, from the way they choose what goes on the shelves to the way they answer every question with so much knowledge and patience. Whenever I’m looking for hard-to-find cocktail ingredients or just want something delicious that’s sourced locally, this is the first place I go. I always leave feeling inspired. I totally recommend grabbing a bottle and maybe some pizza or a beer (while you’re at it) for your next lunch or dinner. Pro tip: ask them what they’re loving right now. They’ll steer you toward something awesome!

text.text: Great little shop!! I don't live close, was in the neighborhood, and have been wanting to stop in the Seafood Shop after hearing great things.  I came close to closing time, we're talking about 10 minutes before. Regardless with being practically done with their day, I walk in and was delightfully greeted by "C" (we'll call him, bc I can't quite remember). He was very welcoming, showed me around the shop and mentioned they make lobster rolls. I said I'll take one! C explained the roll and I asked if it was possible to make it with no mayo -  I'm more of a Connecticut Style girl and their lobster rolls come Maine Style (a little mayo, celery & chives). C wasn't familiar but was so sweet to make sure he prepared exactly the way I wanted it and together we made it happen! Even though I was the last person, he didn't hang his apron-- he gave a full experience, accommodated me, and educated me about their offerings and their handroll night.  The lobster roll is actually an order for two rolls and a side of chips and came out to be $35. Everything in the shop is well curated. I'll definitely return way before closing time so I can properly shop and pick up some great items. The owners are also Filipino so bonus points as I love to support all our kababayans. Thank you!

text.text: I think I went here too many times in one week. Tried their yellowtail poke salad and it was the freshest yellowtail i had for poke. I also got clams and the person helped me made sure I didn’t have dead clams and gave me open bag and Ice to go (making sure the clams didn’t die during 7 min transit). The clams were delicious same as the octopus and calamari they sell. I also tried their Unagi. Although it says on their menu listing its $17/lb, the price went up to 16.95/ 8oz. Which to me is the same as 99 Ranch prices. Unagi tasted good though. What I really love at this place is their Sushi grade Salmon and Tuna. The cut in Salmon is great because its top to bottom where you get the lean and the fatty part of the salmon. It has great marbling and just melts in your mouth. Same with their Tuna. Super fresh tasting. Seaweed salad is seasoned well. Will definitely try their Oysters next time. I guess i’m just gonna go down the list and try all their seafood since its such a great price and quality.

text.text: I've been coming to Valerie's quite a bit. Their food is quite good; killer quiches and tasty chocolates, albeit a tad expensive. I'd also come for their lattes, but I think things have been changing recently? Last time I went, I was surprised to hear from the cashier that they "don't do espresso drinks" and they stopped serving side salads with their quiches. I'm sure the cashier thought I hadn't been before, but they still had the sign up for lattes and felt mildly dismissed by the comment. This is more of their "retail location," apparently, but it's a bit of a shame because the patio area is cute, and I like how off the path this place is. It's disappointing to see the selection of fresh drinks/food contract, but what they do have is tasty, at least.
