text.text:
I visited Woodcat a couple of times and had good coffee on both occasions. However, I probably prefer its sister coffee shop Dinosaur Coffee further up Sunset Boulevard for its more open and brighter space.

But it's not the dark-tone, cramped space that bothers me the most, it's the lack of enthusiasm, excitement, and exuberance—the energy I got when I first saw their colorful bean bags at another coffee shop—that dissuaded me from visiting more often. The baristas are friendly but seem tired; the drink menu displays no creativity; even the yellow light from a small table lamp makes me feel sleepy and cancels out the caffeination I am there for.

Anyway, I'm probably biased. Echo Park is full of chic, sunny, modern coffee shops, it for sure can use a neighborhood-y, no-frills place like this.

text.text: This is an authentic Taiwanese home-style restaurant. I had saved it after seeing it on social media and finally visited on a weekday evening. The interior reflects the owner’s great sense of style—what could have felt like a small space was cleverly designed to feel cozy and inviting. Sunlight streaming through the windows added warmth to the atmosphere, and surprisingly, the air conditioning kept the space cool and comfortable. The food is simple but flavorful. The noodles in the beef fried noodles dish were wonderfully chewy and had a great bite to them—definitely a standout. The fried rice, on the other hand, was a bit underwhelming. The bun was tasty, but I’d especially recommend the noodles.

text.text:
design + branding for this restaurant is incredibly cool and the food lives up to the art direction quality !!!

beef noodles (while throwing on their spicy home made sauce) had such a perfectly charred authentic flavor to it’s richness and the chewy noodle texture brought it all together. ASMR chewing experience

the tofu + cucumber salad had this intriguing acidic balance to it and super firm small cut tofu texture that paired great with the beef noodles in between bites.

The pork belly bowl was tender, rich and tasty too !!

scallion pancakes with the dipping sauce was yummy, I’m used to a thicker pancake up in the Bay but the crispy thin acted as a chip which I loved.

Fair pricing, everything felt so intentional. Recommended !

The food was amazing to start off with the beef noodles, the steak was tender, and the noodles were flavorful. The wings were some of the freshest and crispiest wings I’ve ever had, add some tableside chili oil to the wings… the fried rice was really solid…. I totally recommend this for all four plates, I spent $61 before tip.

text.text: Was not disappointed by the top rated reviews of Woon, and glad we made the trek over to Filipinotown for a meal here (we walked about an hour from our hotel). The menu is limited but everything we ordered was excellent, including the pork belly rice, beef noodles, five spice chicken wings and ice cream bao (with pandan coconut). Service was friendly and attentive, despite us not giving a tip when we paid cash at the counter when ordering (we tipped at the end of our meal). We're not used to the tipping culture, but this was definitely a meal we were more than happy to tip for. This was our last meal during our stay in LA and so glad it ended on such a satisfying note. Would definitely come back again if we were ever back in LA in the future.

text.text:
Already loved the OG spot, I was so excited to finally catch a day here for brekkie.

The place obviously rocks. From the incredible design, the amazing staff, perfect sized menu, all the way to the small details of the place.

Some people are complaining about portion to prices but like, did you not already see the menu and photos beforehand? And to the edge-lords who always seem to talk about “authenticity” of these places.. they are mostly run by second gen people who are appealing to all audiences while also sharing cultural dishes. If you want 100% authentic just catch a flight to that country.

Not everything on the menu is for me (ex: the French toast was just okay but I know many who absolutely love it) but I still have enjoyed everything I’ve ever tried at either locations.

The staff really make this place what it is too, asides from the food. Always a lovely time at Woon :^)

text.text:
Really good food, great interiors, recommend going when/before they open to avoid waiting in line

How to order: wait in line until you get to the cashier, where you’ll order, receive a table number, and either be seated right away or asked to wait to the side until a table frees up. I recommend grabbing a menu in front while you wait in line so you know what to order when you get to the front.

Brunch is great - the chicken congee and pork chop sandwich are delicious. If you’re already ordering a pork chop sandwich and a milk tea French toast, I’d skip getting an additional bolo bao from the pastry case because it’s the same bolo bao from the pork sandwich and the same oolong custard from the French toast

Dinner is also really good, highly recommend the noodles which have a satisfying chew to them, the chicken wings, and the pork belly bao. They also have a great curation of canned drinks and wine.

text.text: The best hidden sushi market that has been a staple for decades. Many fresh fish options as well as rolls. Take a number from the roll and wait until they call your number. Then you pick your fish and they will cut it up and box it for no additional charge and call your number when it’s ready. There are also many Japanese snacks, seasonings, and desserts. Parking lot in the back is small but usually has open spaces. On Saturday morning it was very busy and took me about 20 minutes to get my order. Small driveway is easy to miss; turn right after the Jack in the Box drive through.

text.text:
An absolute hidden gem in the SGV area. It's so hidden from the street you wouldn't even know it if you don't specifically look for this place. But once you've found it, you'll want to save this in your Google Map for sure.

The sushi here is the freshest ones you can find in the area. Like, the salmon will literally melt on your tongue. Even my wife, who had never wanted to eat raw food in her entire life, love their sushi here.

They have prepackaged sushi boxes in their fridge sections that you can just grab and go. They pack the sushi boxes on the day of so tha quality is still top-notch. If you're looking for the freshest sashimi, then they have a counter section where you can pick the fish you like, and they cut and prep for you on the spot. Either one is a good choice to satisfy your sushi cravings.

They also sell various other stuff in the store such as drinks, alcohols, and snacks. Their selection of sakes are huge. They literally have an entire wall with shelves of different sakes for you to choose.

The parking here is kind of difficult to find since it's a small plaza behind Jack In The Box. Their sushi tend to sell out fast too, especially on the weekends. So make sure to come here bright and early if you want a taste of the awesome sushi they have.

text.text:
The service and atmosphere is great. But when they used the word Asian fusion, I knew it is more like “American” Asia food. The food is all pretty bad and way overpriced!

1) the fried chicken $19 for 5 pieces, the chicken were dried and doesn’t have any taste? They have some salt and lemon aside but it is pretty much bland without it.

2) the fish collar, was undercook the server are nice enough to asked if we like it redone but we are almost done so we didn’t have them redo it. They removed it from the bill. It was not too flavorful as well…

3) the fish with hanian chicken rice. Recreate from the famous hanian chicken, the rice is pretty good and pretty authentic. But the fish…. I’m not sure how to describe it. It is again, tasteless and dried…….

4) duck leg with taro mash. Interesting dish but these two flavor doesn’t taste good together. The duck leg was fried the same way as the fried chicken. The taro mash is fine but is not worth $40.

Overall I would say the service is good and attentive. But I wouldn’t be back for sure. The presentation of food, taste and price point is below average in my standard.

text.text: Tried their brunch for the first time, and it will certainly not be the last time. We ordered a cornmeal mochi pancake, David's arroz caldo, and the breakfast plate. I was worried the pancake would be grainy, and while you can taste the cornmeal, it was good. My friend aptly pointed out the texture was similar to Ethiopian injera so it was light. The highlight though was the persimmon jam on top. The arroz caldo is (Filipino) congee, and it hit the spot, warm and soothing. For the breakfast plate, we went with (hangar) steak and eggs. The steak was cooked to a perfect medium rare. The scrambled eggs were soft and fluffy. That brick of hashed browns was crispy and light, which made us wonder if it was perhaps potatoes and jicama. It wasn't too busy when we arrived, but there was a wait when we were almost done. The service was overall good. They definitely rushed us at the end to free up the table but not to the point of being rude, so I still give them 5 stars on service. The seating isn't the most comfortable, and the tables felt a bit too close to other diners, but this isn't enough to keep me away from the amazing food.

text.text:
Yoboseyo Superette is a delightful hidden gem blending the charm of Korean culture with modern flair. Nestled in a cozy spot, it offers incredible coffee brewed with beans from none other than Dulce, known for its smooth flavors at the USC Village. The shop's vibe is a fusion of traditional Korean elements with a contemporary twist, making it both inviting and unique.

Beyond the amazing coffee, Yoboseyo offers a wide array of Korean-inspired foods, snacks, and even accessories. Each item seems carefully curated to provide an authentic Korean experience right in the heart of the city. Whether you're in for a quick coffee break or looking to explore some unique Korean goodies, Yoboseyo Superette promises a warm, welcoming atmosphere and a rich array of choices.

If you haven’t visited yet, you're definitely missing out on a quaint spot that brings a little piece of Korea to your everyday life. Perfect for coffee lovers and culture enthusiasts alike

text.text:
Hard to believe that this is the first dedicated boba shop that's opened up at the USC Village! The area has needed a major facelift in the boba department and Yoboseyo holds its own to that regard.

The shop operates both as a boba shop as well as a Korean snack store. Being on a college campus, they definitely had non-dairy milk options which made my heart happy. I ordered a Mango Matcha Latte with Oat Milk and Boba, and my drink came out great. You aren't able to adjust the sweetness level with the puree drinks but that's probably what made it taste so good.

They're opened fairly late which is great if you need to stop by for higher quality boba in the area.

text.text:
I love how well stocked, clean, and wonderfully organized this store is. I was greeted by the sweetest person named Klove. While they were very busy with multiple customers, I was asked if I needed help. I appreciated that because I needed a bread maker, and I was brought out the one I wanted.
This store offers a lot of products. Everything from utensils and professional knives, mixers and bread makers, pots and pans, seasonings and oils, cutting boards, and cups, and so much more!
What really sold me on the store was the owner, Marguerite, came out and talked with me for a bit about the store and what they offer and all kinds of other great stuff. I really enjoyed the conversation. The moment a customer walked in, Marguerite was very attentive to the customer and answering all the questions. To see an owner of a shop involved in their products and customers needs made the place feel even better. And to top it- Klove took my stuff that I purchased to my car because it was so heavy. Kindness like this has earned a lifelong customer! I'll see you guys soon.

text.text:
I was on a damn mission to find another house plant, because why not?
Hobbies are hobbies.
Sue me. (Please do not. Not cool. Chill out.)
Lunchboxx was my meal of choice (Top-notch-schtuff), so I stopped at Denver Central Market to pick up my food. I’m a loyalist for another botanical shop, but, when parking, I saw Recital with it’s plant-lined storefront…
The chlorophyll gods were calling my name. I hadn’t heard/read/seen anything about the place before.
Upon walking inside and doing 4 to 7 seconds of reconnaissance, I caved and admitted my insecurities when it came to not having a proverbial green thumb.
I was immediately greeted with helpful suggestions, tips, hints, and genuine interest in the hobby.
The two people steering the helm (apologies for not knowing names) obviously knew what they were talking about, and they were both actively listening to how genuinely f**ked I was at taking care of plants. We all joked about over-misting our chartreuse-shaded, inanimate dirt children.

ANYSPRAY, long-story-long, just go to Recital. Just go.
Thoughtful people.
Buyable things.
Warm atmosphere.
Extremely deficient in bad vibes.

text.text:
Kanpai to Bon Bon Market!

Such a cute name for a mini Asian grocery store. Actually it's more like a boutique inside. They sell plants too! While bon bon means "chocolate covered candy", I didn't see any candy browsing through. That'd be nice if they sold some though.

There are specialty products imported from various Asian countries. So if you love dining at those kind of restaurants, you may find your favorite ingredients or SAUCE here.

Did you know butter can be made from sesame? Well ther is such a thing - interesting! Like peanut and almond butter...

More so, I like their beer, wine and sake collections. I'm highly recommending the Kyoto Matcha IPA, an excellent quality beer. "Ipa ipa hooray!"

text.text:
We arrived before opening on a Saturday and waited in line for 40 minutes (which we expected) and were able to order coffee from a Pony Coffee truck, which was delicious.
Once inside, incredible smells overtook us and we lost the plot. Ordered so many treats! The single best thing, other than the bread, was the service. Cat and co. were calm, patient, and cheerful as they served us despite the pressure of so many hungry patrons. The didn’t appear ruffled in the least- a rare feat in the service industry! The bread was still warm; we enjoyed it in the car. We are so glad we were able to enjoy Country Bird Bakery while in Tulsa.

text.text: This was such a fun experience! We got there a little before they open and we waited in line about an hour maybe a little more. It was drizzling and they provided umbrellas for us to use as we waited. The building is very small with maybe 10-15 people inside at one time. The service is super fast once you're inside. They have everything laid out in plain view and you just let them know what you want and they bag it up for you. They have so many options from plain croissants, filled pastries, flavored butters, fresh sourdough, and take and bake dough. They are open every other Thursday which is usually less busy but they may sell out sooner. I feel there is more variety on Saturdays. Follow their Facebook and Instagram where they post the offerings available that week. I tried the maple blonde which was so amazing! I also got an espresso supreme but my favorite was the pecan double baked croissant 😋If you love bread you HAVE TO GO HERE!

text.text:
The night before, while I was at PW’s Bar & Grill, I was told I absolutely had to visit Fariner Bakery the next morning for a cinnamon roll. When I came up to the bakery’s display case and saw those cinnamon rolls, I knew I had to get one. The cinnamon roll was everything I hoped for—soft, rich, and full of flavor. The cappuccino was equally delightful, perfectly crafted, and the ideal complement to the pastry.

With a large communal table at the center, it was the perfect spot to sit down, savor a cappuccino, and enjoy a delicious pastry. The staff was incredibly friendly and knowledgeable, making the entire experience even more enjoyable.

I also learned that Fariner Bakery hosts a special Apero Hour on weekends, offering cocktails, snacks, and a delightful evening experience. Overall, my visit to Fariner Bakery was a wonderful experience.

I may not know if I’ll have the chance to return to Ashland, but for anyone staying at the RV campground or passing through, it’s definitely worth a stop.

I came here on Easter to treat myself, and I’m so glad I did. It wasn’t as packed as usual, so I snagged a great seat outside on the patio where the breeze was just perfect. The music matched the calm vibe, making the whole atmosphere super relaxing.

From the moment I walked in, the staff made me feel welcomed. Shoutout to Matthew, who recommended the Asparagus Agedashi(it was absolutely delicious and vegan) and to Adam, who helped me out with the vendor items and suggested the vegan carrot cake (also amazing).

Everything I tried was flavorful and thoughtfully prepared. I even ordered another Asparagus Agedashi to go; it was that good. Definitely a memorable Easter treat!

text.text: Parker and Scott is a cute store with fun eats, unique gifts, and lots of options for sustainable living. They also make an effort to support locally-made products, like pottery, and local businesses generally. One of my favorite features about them is their contract with Ridwell so that patrons can bring in their plastic bags that are not recycled by the City of Austin (snack bags, for instance) to be recycled; for your effort and to encourage you in this up-leveling of your recycling game, they reward you with 10% off when you do so. Thank you Parker and Scott!

text.text: Did a Google "Coffee near me" search when we were in the area and decided to stop in.... I am glad we did. This is more than just a coffee shop. They offer locally produced take and bake food, as well as wines, other interesting items. We opted for the coffee only and were impressed. Their coffee was good and HOT (which it usually never is at independent shops). The staff was friendly, helpful, and attentive. The atmosphere is very cozy and bright. If we are in the area again and are looking for good coffee we will be stopping in. Give them a try.... you won't regret it. Parking may be a little iffy at peak times, but it's worth the effort.

text.text:
When it comes to the coffee, the drinks are solid and enjoyable. While not a mind-blowing, "best I've ever had" kind of experience, the quality is good and the unique botanical syrups are a nice touch that sets their menu apart.

​What truly makes Rose Hip Market stand out is its carefully selected retail collection. The shelves are stocked with an array of beautifully curated home accessories, gourmet pantry items, puzzles, and more. This focus on supporting local artisans and vendors is a significant part of the market's charm and mission. It makes the store a genuine one-stop-shop where you can grab a decent cup of coffee, a quick and delicious meal from their grab-and-go selection (including prepared meals from local vendors), and find a unique gift for a friend or yourself.

text.text:
Ándale Market is a super cute bodega with an emphasis on local, sustainable, and artisanal items. They manage to squeeze a lot of great stuff in a tiny space: pantry goods, kitchen cookbooks and accessories, body care and period products, candles, a chocolate, charcuterie and cheese cooler, fun bevvies cooler, fresh flowers, and freshly made Public Quality Bread.

My favorite product to buy here is Chilee Oil, the spicy version of their premium recipe (which used avocado oil). I like knowing that, when I buy it here, I’m supporting not just one but two great local small businesses.

The store has a well-deserved reputation of supporting the community. When Foxtrot unexpectedly closed their Chicago storefronts earlier this year and left their vendors with unpaid invoices and surplus product, Ándale invited impacted local vendors to use their patio space for pop-up markets. It was such a wholesome display of community care in a cut-throat capitalist world that can I rarely see as a consumer.

The one recommendation and opportunity for improvement I have to offer: the front entry is not wheelchair ♿️ accessible because there is a step at the threshold that is too tall to cross with most mobility aids. It would be great to see this turned into an accessible up-ramp with an automatic door.

text.text:
I’m always excited to make my trek across town specifically to visit this Andersonville neighborhood gem. The shelves are lively and curated and spark the imagination. It feels like ages since Ive traveled but the world-ranging products found on these market shelves take me back, let me reminisce and also spark the imagination to take new staples and treats home. It’s the perfect selection to stock your pantry, find an “I deserve it” or assemble a fun selection to let someone know that they are just as special to you (the gifting options are immense!). I love that the shelves are largely arranged as a bit of a world map. Gift-giving Italiano? Several shelves will readily relate. World-wide wonder? Pick one from each shelf and you won’t be disappointed.

Take some time, Andale won’t rush you, instead enjoy the journey (from front to back, shelf to shelf…)

text.text: My favorite ice cream in all of Chicago. Homemade fresh every single day so when they run out that’s it! I love that this is a small business with so much heart. The flavors are incredible. The goat cheese cashew caramel is my go to and a fan favorite. The Italian Cookie tastes exactly like biscoff cookies. Serving size is perfect. Each scoop is not too big nor too small, and every bite is packed with flavor. They have amazing options for vegans too, so many dairy free options and days where they only serve dairy free! Staff are super sweet, there is lovely little outdoor patio area with string lights and tables under shady trees. My favorite spot to grab ice cream with friends (or solo!) and sit awhile. I have been eating Black Dog for the last 5 years and I can’t recommend it enough.

Best sandwich in Baltimore, hands down. This place is a MUST if you’re in the area, and even if you’re not honestly. Ingredients are fresh and recipes are thoughtfully and creatively prepared. I had the brisket roast beef sandwich which came on a plate with fresh sweet berries and chips. I’m going to dream about that sandwich until I can have it again. Owner Rob was incredibly kind and personable as well. We enjoyed walking around the shop and found a lot of really cool grocery items to buy like salty pistachio spread and lavender honey hazelnut butter.

It was a delightful and delectable experience all around! We’ll be back ASAP.

Edited to add a photo from our return visit - it didn’t disappoint!

text.text:
I am so glad this place popped up on my maps when I searched for “bakery”. After reading reviews and looking at the photos, I told my boyfriend that if we visit this place, I’ll just be jealous we don’t have something like this back home (in NYC, nonetheless).

And I was right - I walked into the storefront and found things I wanted, and hadn’t even made it five feet in.

You can sense that the market items were selected on purpose; Sylva knew the origin story of each brand and what they’re known for. We picked up a salted caramel pandan syrup, and two different hot sauces.

For the cooked food - we devoured a ham and cheese croissant, and an apple and cheese pastry (that I still think about today). We also got a chicken meat pie for later and it was delicious - lots of flavor.

This is a place I could spend a few hours in and move from breakfast to lunch to early cocktail and dinner.
We are planning another weekend trip to Baltimore and can’t wait to come back.

text.text:
I really enjoy Each Peach. It definitely is pricey, but I have also never encountered kitchen ingredients that weren't of stellar quality. You can find about 95% of everything you could need for your cooking/kitchen at this little market (fyi, it's cramped!), including fresh hot sandwiches, soups, etc., and everything is typically a unique specialty brand from elsewhere in the country, nearby or far, as well as around the world. Soap from Palestine, salt from the UK, cheeses galore from dairy farms around the world, and more. I love their French butter, local produce, Italian flours and cheeses, Grecian olive oils, and their chocolate and coffee items.

They do not have their own butcher but do sell a good basic selection (frozen) from really high quality vendors.

Because of all the imported brands or small-business farmers they purchase from, yes, prices will be higher. Focus on buying what you *want* here, not necessarily everything you *need* (although you most certainly can, of course).

They also have a great selection of local fresh breads and pastries in the mornings. I believe bread is from Baked Joint(?) and croissants are from the excellent local DC bakery/café Saku Saku Flakerie (there might be an upcharge on these, as one reviewer noted). They also have donuts (not sure where from but they're satisfying), and great local bagels.

Overall, yes, expense will be a factor here. But selection has never disappointed me. I find myself always going back for specific items that I can't typically find elsewhere (and that are just too good to go back to anything different).

Think of Each Peach Market as like a record store or "greatest hits" playlist of unique songs by smaller artists from around the country and beyond...but for groceries.

Just bought a croissant for $5.75 a piece. Last time (a few weeks ago) was $5.00 or $5.25. When I asked the reason for the almost 10% increase in price, I was told that “croissants are a luxury product”. Poor customer service with a strong attitude, especially for a store that claims to be affordable and neighborhood oriented.

Found the same croissant at Saku Saku Flakerie in Cleveland Park - $4.95, instead of $5.75.

text.text:
An absolute foodie destination. There are two sides to the shop: a large liquor store with an emphasis on hard liquor, and the area I made purchases in, the cheese shop. Cheese is my thing, and I was delighted to find they had a vast assortment with many items that are difficult to find in the US. Many cheeses had informational cards. The monger was quite helpful and patient as I made my selections, custom cutting many of the blocks for me.

The shop also had a large range of accompaniments--jams, honey, crackers, pickles, butter--and a deli menu complete with a small case of delectable-looking baked goods.

text.text:
The 44th and France Cheese and Meat Shop shares the same building. It has been providing local Linden Hills residents with its fine cheese selection since 2001. I can to know it while being a manager at DURR LTD years back.

While I typically buy there for its cheese and fine meats, it also sells sandwiches, charcuterie, gift baskets, grocery, and baked goods like pies. The deli also offers and extensive selection of wine, spirits, and ready to go gourmet foods. They have a very helpful and knowledgeable staff to assist with selections. I called ahead to learn if they have my favorite imported, fresh milk stilton and L’Amuse Gouda cheeses on hand.

L'Amuse Signature Gouda is the product of a close partnership between several Gouda vendors, mainly Cono and Lutjewinkel – I like it when it’s aged 2 years or more.

The staff offers tips like “let you cheese come to room temperature a half hour before serving”. When I’m preparing for a real special event in rooms without climate control, it is worth it to serve the cheese at just the right temperature.

You can pick up Melts, Salads, Soups and Sandwiches to go. For example, I like the Curry Chicken Salad Sandwich and the Tomato Gazpacho Soup. They are well-staffed, so if there is a line, no worries - most likely you'll be checking out next.

It is also an ideal place to pick up Gifts of Taste for special friends and family. I recently gave a Letterpress Ashanti Dark Mint Chocolate bar as a gift and they loved it!

Other great cheeses include: La Retorta, Rond de Cher, Chebris, Swallow Tail, Rispens, Cabriolait, and Markle Gouda. Since it is on a busy corner, go around to the back where there is ample parking.

text.text:
We just wanted to take a moment to thank HEX Superette from the bottom of our hearts for all the effort they put into helping us plan and organize our baby shower in January. It was absolutely perfect!

Please extend our deepest thanks to the entire front and back of house team at HEX. Every detail was seamless, and the food was beyond delicious. We feel so lucky to have such a wonderful gem in our neighborhood, and we were thrilled to introduce it to friends and family who had never been before. It made the celebration even more special that they all loved the Superette!

Our hearts are full as we prepare to welcome our baby. Your work made the shower even more meaningful, and we are truly grateful for all that you did to make the day so memorable.
Thank you again for everything!

text.text:
HEX Superette is an absolute gem. Visit them immediately!
The bar is so pretty & the market is the best selection of food & local goods. I love bringing friends for drinks or dinner- it’s just such a relaxing & fun vibe. It’s also a great spot during the day to work if you need a get away spot.

The food is outstanding! I’m absolutely obsessed with the Kimchi Enchiladas (beef or mushroom- they’re both so good), the Grazing Board, and the Flight to Portugal (featuring the best tinned fish!) The cocktails are some of my favorite in Baltimore!! Plus I love the Brine Back shot- so fun.

The outdoor patio area is also so great- our dog loved it & it makes for the perfect chill Sunday lunch spot.

I recommend HEX for all of the things- it’s seriously amazing!!💜

text.text:
Awesome store! Clean, well organized, with a nice atmosphere. I like how everything is cleanly displayed to allow customers to browse at their own pace without being over-stimulated. It also shows that items were carefully curated.

They have teamed up with local artists and producers to bring authentic art, food, and more to the neighborhood. I am excited to have a walkable spot for honey, nordic crackers, tinned fish, dukkah-like seasoning, and local pottery.  They also host fun workshops.

Andrew is super friendly and happy to help when you have questions. I enjoyed learning about their different snacks and NA spirits. He also showed that they support their neighboring businesses by sharing information about what's opening soon.

displayName.text: Kruse Markit Bistro, Coffee and Wine Bar

text.text:
The only reason I haven’t already written this review is because I don’t want this place to get overrun. 😭
Kruse Markit offers European coffee shop vibes right on Nicollet Ave. The staff is friendly, attentive, and honest. I once left my AirPods there and 2 days later went back and the same staff member had saved them and gave them back to me when I asked if they’d seen them. Coffee is stellar. Food is incredible - flavorful with lots of options for vegan and vegetarians. The wine list is never ending and the staff can recommend some winners even to the snobbiest of winos.

text.text:
I’ll lead with the good: the food! I’ve had breakfast and dinner here. Both meals were good. Great toast. Good salads. Pastas we’re tasty.

Service is a bit aloof. There’s no charm or attention to detail in it though. It felt perfunctory, as though no one was happy to be there. No one was mean, just vacant.

Atmosphere: it’s beautiful in here. No detail left unconsidered. Seats are great.
Fans are a cool touch. Everything is great. But it’s dead. Sterile. Feels like a Pinterest Board restaurant come to life.
The word cool appears all over the place, menus, walls, website, cups. And it’s literal. It’s trying to be cool, but cool isn’t something you can define yourself as. Cool happens organically. It’s trying to hard. Do less. Say less. Be less.

text.text:
Found the Rice Market recently when needing to kill some time before a Lip Lab appointment. Had no idea that this lovely hidden gem was tucked under the Rice Asian restaurant on 14th St. in the NW section of DC. Rice in addition to the restaurant has a specialty market filled with all of the things including Sake, Asian snacks, cookbooks, sauces, teas and other items. Rice Market also hosts cooking classes and events in this space.

It was fun just exploring their curated selections to see what Rice had in store. If you want something special for a home cooked Asian meal, I suggest that you stop by Rice Market. They’re likely to have what you need. You might check out the market before or after you grab a bite at the restaurant upstairs.

For a quick snack, I opted for a Kani nigiri from the market. It was tasty & a perfect small bite while on the go.

text.text:
They carry the widest selection of sake in town, perhaps more than 100 varieties. It is also notable that they have an extended portfolio of Oregon wines by producers including Goodfellow, Shiba Wichern, and Violin.

Rice Factory's rice is the best available in the country, and each has an indication of the milled date (fairly recent) and we know their crops are fresh and not oxidated much.

Rice Market offers ready-to-eat food, including Onigiri and Thai food.

There's a premiums fresh sashimi section in the rice market, too.

text.text:
An attractive brunch spot with highs and lows, tucked in to one of Belle Meade's strip malls. It's worth your time. The modern interior, with its stylish tile floor and open vibes, is very comfortable.  The food we tried was gorgeous, with the salmon toast draped in artfully sculpted watermelon radish and dill, and the quiche presented via a tall robust slice next to a mound of salad. We also tried the jiggly soufflé pancake, which was tasty, light, and fun, though a bit dry vs. the eggy-ness I expected. Big bonus points for the chai-spiced syrup though. On the downside, the egg sandwich on a "Japanese milk bun" was more basic than described. After many trips to Japan, I can safely say this is merely a decent standard brioche burger bun. You need to elevate a lot more to use the "J.M.B." title. Onion jam is always welcome though.

Service was a bit forgetful and slow, though well-intentioned. We had to re-request a coffee, ask for a refill, and for salt & pepper. It's a very young staff and they could learn to be a bit more solicitous. But they are forgiven easily. Overall, the effort to compose a refined alternative to standard west Nashville brunch options is appreciated, and I'll be back to check on their progress. Next time, for the vibes and to try the sandwich menu.

text.text:
More Than a Wine Store — It’s Family

I’ve been going to Triangle Wine in Cary for over 10 years, and I honestly don’t know why it’s taken me this long to write a review — this place is truly special.

The owners are wonderful and treat me like family every time I walk through the door. One of the most meaningful gestures was when they gifted me use of the back room to host my out-of-town friends and family the day before my baby shower. It meant so much — and it’s just one example of how kind and generous they are.

The staff is always attentive and welcoming. They know my wine preferences and never steer me wrong — their recommendations are always spot on! The wine selection is extensive, with something for every palate, and their events are not only top notch but also incredibly cost-friendly.

Triangle Wine isn’t just a place to buy wine — it’s a place where community, connection, and quality come together. Can’t say enough great things about it!

CHEERS

Wild Love Bakery is absolutely delightful! I got a green tea oat milk matcha latte, which might have been the best I’ve ever had—so creamy and flavorful. text.text:
I spent most of my life in this area and have been thrilled to welcome Cafe Mornings into my routine.

The drinks are stellar, the atmosphere of the dining area and patio are serene, and the food is amazing. Every detail of the business is thoughtful and intentional, and the owners and staff are always so friendly. The food and pastries have always come out quick in my experience, but I wouldn’t mind waiting five times as long as I normally do.

There is no better breakfast in the Catskills, and possibly on earth, than the Mornings bacon and corn cheese sandwich, washed down with a strawberry matcha latte.

text.text: This cute little coffee shop that is tucked away into the rolling hills that are strewn with every color of a crisp autumn day that echoes every crunch of a leaf into the air and peaked mountains that are awaiting their first arrival of snowfall to grace them with a touch of winter was exactly what was needed on a fine Sunday morning. It seems like a bit of a modern haven seems to be nestled into a town that is frozen in time with antique stores and old-fashioned laundromats surrounding it, and the serenity that encompasses you as you walk inside to peaceful music that lulls you into a comatose before the food and coffee do highlights this even more. The seasonal iced caramel apple butter latte that I got gave me all the nostalgia in the world of a time in the yonder years of the magic of the fall time full of apple picking, pumpkin carving, and innocence galore, and the surprise mini print vending machine that they had of tiny art done by a local artist was the icing on the cake (or the whipped cream on the latte, if we're sticking to a foodie theme here). This experience wrapped up my final morning in the Catskills with a little bow, and I truly believe it would be worth a day-trip just to return here if I don't have a weekend-trip planned again any time soon. Thank you for the beautiful time! :))

text.text:
The place is loud with live music and a bar. You can get drinks in the attached bar or at the bar in the dance space. There is a hot dog stand outside and across the street as well.

Entry is cash only, unless you book tickets  beforehand with card. They do have an ATM at the entertance, for anyone who forgets cash cover.

Friendly bouncers and staff that are kind and helpful when needed.

There is a live DJ and during event nights and sometimes balloons and cotton candy available.

Bathrooms are generally clean but the bathrooms are fairly small, so there is often a wait as the night picks up.

Crowd doesn't usually pick up until about 10/10:30, but doors open at 9:00.

Free self-serve water is available at all times.

There is also a photo booth and a small set of couches and chairs to lounge on.

Occasional strobe lights and dim lighting can make navigation a challenge for some.

The only drawback is the place can be a bit dirty with sticky floors and rips and tears in the furniture. But...that just gives it character.

Plan to be a bit warm or dress lightly. There is a giant fan blowing, but the dance floor gets quite hot.

Overall a fun place to go, especially on theme nights. Everyone is welcome and the atmosphere is friendly.

Such a fun, fabulous, friendly place! I had not been to DFP in several years, decided to journey there seeking some fresh seasonal pasta. Like the proverbial child in a candy store, I was enthralled by all of the fare options, including amazing sandwiches (chose the fig and prosciutto among so many tantalizing choices), desserts, (a must-try is the Portokalopita,
an out-of-this-world cardamom confection-staff told me people come here just for this delicacy), unusual wines, so much more. What pulls it all together into a rare and wonderful overall experience is the exceptional customer service. To a person, everyone working there was so kind and helpful. Going to Dave’s Fresh Pasta today was one of my best adult field trips ever!

text.text:
Three or four star butcher shop/deli but five star sandwich shop. Their sandwiches are reasonably priced and incredibly tasty especially the burger and anything they have with bacon in it.

I am forgiving a lot by giving them five stars but they seriously have one of the best burgers in NYC at any price point but especially for 15 bucks. The meat is super high quality, well seasoned and has tons of cheese. The size is impressive for the price too, it's a meaty smash burger that puts 7th Street to shame.

Not every sandwich on the menu is a knockout, the roast beef has like no meat on it for some reason but their bacon is incredible and the breakfast sandwiches like the green eggs are solid. Love the BLT with heirloom tomatoes when it's in season.

Now for the bad, the tips at the register are crazy, like 18% is the lowest tip suggestion and you get hit up for a tip for every order even charcuterie, meat, or grocery items. I gotta push back on this, it always annoys me when counter service places try to squeeze tips out of customers.

Their charcuterie is not the best and very expensive. I haven't been blown away by anything. The selection isn't great,and most things are not worth the price. Their Iberico Chorizo is solid but a lot of their charcuterie are not that interesting or curated in any way. Just a hodge podge of overpriced meats. I assume many of them are local because there would be no other reason to carry them.

A lot of the stuff they carry in the store part of the business is not worth the prices they charge but as a sandwich spot they are five stars all day. Also, be warned that the sandwiches take forever to make especially on the weekends.

I also really like the truffle chips and a chai latte, plus checking out shop offerings - there’s always something new. Abbie and her crew provide exceptional offerings - enjoy!

I shared with her my experience with traditional matcha,, having experienced it many many years ago when I visited my classmate and his wife in Tokyo. Also I mentioned my selection of matcha which I order from overseas. She mentioned that there was a shortage ( from those who prefer to drink a matcha latte instead)  and I said that probably doesnt affect me as i had stocked up on matcha during Black Friday last year and only consume a cup a day.
I highly recommend visiting Kinka.

text.text:
Kitty’s is a charming little spot conveniently located right next to the Amtrak station in Hudson, which makes it a great stop whether you're coming into town or heading out. The location alone is a major plus.
The shop offers a wide variety of items, ranging from pantry goods to drinks and baked treats. However, when it comes to fresh food options—especially in the morning—the menu is a bit limited. In fact, the only breakfast meal on offer is an egg and cheese sandwich. That said, it’s a solid one—well-made, satisfying, and flavorful. It also comes with the option of a hash brown on the side, which I definitely recommend. Crispy, well-seasoned, and just the right portion. I do believe that they are priced on the bit of the higher end.

They also had a selection of baked goods on display. While I didn’t get the chance to try them, they looked fresh and genuinely tempting. As tasty as they look, I wasn’t willing to pay what I thought was an excessive price for baked goods that weren’t even coming from the bakery.

Overall, Kitty’s is worth a visit, especially if you're looking for a quick, tasty bite before hopping on a train or exploring Hudson. Just don’t expect a full brunch menu—come for the quality, not the quantity.

text.text:
Popped in to LB Kitchen for lunch on a Tuesday afternoon around 12:30. I immediately loved the whole vibe of the restaurant. There is a refrigerated section with grab and go food options along with a well curated drink selection as well as a significant pantry section with healthy snack, treats, protein bars etc. We placed our order at the counter and were able to snag one of only a handful of indoor tables.

I should honestly be removing one star at this point because our salads took a full 30 minutes to come out. Tables that ordered waaaay after us were getting their food but I ended up enjoying my food so much that I don't want to deduct the star.

I had the kale caesar, add jammy egg and sweet potato, dressing on the side and my husband had the LB bowl, add chicken. The bowls are a little on the pricey side especially with the add ons but if I lived in Portland I would be ordering from here all of the time!

text.text: Sometimes… it all comes together and the magic happens. As a former NYC restaurant owner, I know how hard it is to maintain a cohesive vision that shines through the entire dining experience from first look to dessert. The building is beautiful, inside and out. The adjacent bottle shop is a charming convenience and lends a village feel to the approach. Inside the space is divided between a warm taverna style area and a soaring light, minimal industrial dinning area. Everything is tasteful and in its right place. Service was extraordinary. The entire staff moves in calm, graceful choreography attending to guests with warmth and attentiveness. Sophia, our server,  created an instant bond and made us feel like regulars and old friends as only the best of front of house staff can do. Beer list is tight and on point (don’t sleep on the Baby Kittens from Fat Orange Cat). Wine list is broad and well constructed. Cocktails list was creative and balanced with a stellar mocktail option. The menu is well put together and features the perfect meeting of new American and asian influences. Standouts were the duck bao (which after one bite, I looked at Beth and said “ooohhh! That’s MY food exactly”), the shrimp burger (slightly spicy with Vietnamese vibes) to the roasted 1/2 chicken with togarashi. Flavors were bold and inventive. Everything we ate was cooked and plated perfectly. I rarely end a meal with nothing to critique, but, well, I have nothing but superlatives here. Do note that the kitchen closes around 8:30 PM even on weekends

Kinderhook is a real gem of a town, and the entire restaurant/ art collective that houses The Aviary, Morningbird, and The Nest is a standout.

text.text:
Japanese café located behind a small gourmet grocer with mellow, modern drinks.

Stumbled upon this place while wandering the neighborhood in search of coffee. From the outside, it looked like just another curated grocery store, but tucked in the back was a quiet little cafe. No indoor seating in the cafe, just two small tables near the entrance and a few outside.

Between the two drinks I tried—the Brown Sugar Coffee and the Iced Black Sesame Foam Hoji—the latter was my favorite. One of the employees suggested I try the Brown Sugar Coffee as a latte, but I opted for it black. In hindsight, I probably should’ve taken their advice. It ended up tasting more like a sweetened Dunkin' coffee than a refined house special.

The hoji, though, was fantastic. An ultra-creamy hojicha latte topped with black sesame milk foam. Hojicha and black sesame flavors overlapped a bit, but overall, it was a soft, nutty echo that blended well with the roasted tea notes without any graininess.

If you’re into Japanese-style café drinks with a modern twist, this one’s worth checking out.

text.text:
Absolutely stunning, magnificently decorated  in which one feels, they traveled half way around the world to China.
An assortment of many useful items, perhaps some hidden treasures.
For anyone and everyone, who appreciates the mysteries and realities of the far East.

Again,  as my first master would teach, it's only a secret as long as you have no knowledge of it.
Well kinda, not necessarily completely so,
or accurate for the general public.
Because truthfully,  there are still many,  tremendously deep secrets, to the totality of the deepest reality.
Unfortunately, there are prohibitions to guard the mysteries of life.
However, here you may find some clues,
if you're willing to climb some mountains.  And most importantly must be the right person.

A perfect example would be the decades, the smartest man in history, Confucius, spent looking for the highest knowledge.
(He was the smartest man because he discovered and completed the laws of relativity, almost 2500 years before Einstein.)
Therefore, if you are new to the search/quest of the highest knowledge, this is the perfect place to start.
Clue: follow the Seven Stars. 💜☯️💝
Absolutely Like 👍👍👍👍👍👍👍👍

text.text: This Chelsea Market shop sells a variety of Asian foods, both prepared meals/snacks and pantry items. There are different stations to place your order and pick up depending on what you’re ordering. My friend and I ordered bubble tea. I got a cocoa oolong milk tea with pearls and she got the Chelsea drink which is strawberry milk. I thought my tea was really good, the perfect balance of tea with smooth cocoa, not too sweet (I got 25% sweetness which is the minimum level for this drink). The pearls were fresh and still warm in a lightly sweet syrup. My friend said her Chelsea drink tasted good but was really heavy (I didn’t try it). The two workers there were friendly and the turnaround time for the drinks after ordering was pretty fast. Pearl River Mart doesn’t have its own seating, but there are other general seating areas in the market.

text.text:
Stock Culinary Goods is the cooking store to end all other cooking stores!

Every time I go in, the staff are incredibly helpful and knowledgeable, making every visit nothing short of delightful. Their selection is unmatched—Rancho Gordo beans (a cult favorite and nearly impossible to find in stores), beautifully designed Kinto mugs from Japan in every size and color, locally milled flours from Maine, and even Rhode Island classics like Wright’s Dairy coffee milk. They have it ALL!

Every corner of the shop is thoughtfully curated with the best culinary goods, and the variety is second to none. There’s no place on Hope Street I enjoy being *whisked away into more! (*There’s a whisk flag outside to beckon you into the store when they’re open, so if you see it, let yourself be whisked in too!)

text.text:
Nice Brunch in the countryside.

Got this place recommended by a colleague and came for brunch this past weekend. We arrived a little after noon, and despite being well outside any major town, the restaurant was completely packed. The only open spot was an outdoor table swarmed by wasps. We agreed to take it, but the staff kindly moved us indoors as soon as a table opened up.

The menu here leaned into that familiar farm-to-table, ingredient-driven fusion style you’d commonly find in bigger cities. The dinner menu looked more inventive and truer to their philosophy, and we wished we had time to stay in the area to try it. The upside of brunch, though, was getting to try a few items from their bakery section.

We started off with the seared banana bread, and it was the best griddled version I’ve had. Denser and less crumbly than most, with layers of honey, olive oil, salt, and espresso all working together seamlessly.
Next was the cauliflower agrodolce, which every nearby table seemed to order. The stewed beans in the agrodolce sauce were comforting and familiar, while the fioretto cauliflower (my first time trying it) maintained its crunch even after steaming.

In the Chicken & Waffle, the waffle was meh but the chicken & slaw were fantastic. They used fennel and ginger aioli to give it a more distinctive aroma, and it really worked well with the chili garlic maple glaze on the chicken.

On the side, we also tried the cod chowder, a lighter, herbier take on the usual New England style. The broth was clean and brothy, and while the cod itself was a tad rubbery, I liked the refreshing finish. Only thing we didn’t like were the pancakes. Not bad, just plain compared to everything else on the table.

Would definitely come back for dinner next time we’re in the area.

I def recommend trying it out if you have not.

Limited exterior seating onsite is a bit loud with traffic, but it is connected to the AC Hotel which makes it easy to find some space in there. Great quality coffee and reasonably priced for the location downtown. Check hours to be sure they’re open & read parking signs downtown. If I worked closer I’d be a regular. 🤙🏼
